<a name="newsitem965755793,24432,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Norrathian Historical Events</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Oakgrove Fallingleaf  (<a href="mailto:mhoerrner@hibernia.com" class="credit2">mhoerrner@hibernia.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
I begin this editorial with a quote from Gordon Wrinn:<br><br>"It was a 'big event' as you suggest. Several things happened all over<br>Norrath across all the servers in the days leading up to the opening of the<br>Hole. I am sorry that you missed them."<br><br>This was in response to a player who asked about the Hole and why it was not<br>a world-effecting event.  Verant, of course, ran GM events to publicize this<br>event, but often, these quests are held in such a way that only a few<br>characters (few=30 or less) on a server.  Granted, this quest, and several<br>others - "Rending of the Veil," "Child of Hate," "Al-Kabor," "The Blooding<br>of Kithicor" - were all fantastic quests, sometimes a bit out of hand, that<br>represent the artistry and imagination contained within the Verant<br>community.  However, being that these are historical quests that have a<br>bearing on the entire community of a server, they are woefully inadequate<br>with regard to addressing a server populace as a whole.  Can this situation<br>be rectified?<br><br>Sure it can.  Is it worth the investment?  Maybe.  Most likely, as far as<br>the players at large are concerned.  We crave, as a populace, deeper<br>interaction with the world around us in EQ.  Yet, we are usually faced with<br>NPCs that mirror cardboard stand-ups at movie theaters rather than actual<br>creatures with an AI.  We need more persistent characters who can relate<br>information to us.<br><br>As far as widespread information is concerned, EQ might take a lesson from<br>Asheron's Call's town crier situation in which players can interact with a<br>series of informational NPCs through bribes and speech.  This is a minor<br>touch, but is a great way to disseminate information.  I am not thrilled<br>with these NPCs either, but Verant could easily expand on the idea and<br>develop ways for players to learn important facts (via more quests) about<br>world-changing events.<br><br>As for persistent NPCs, Verant has a massive Guide force at its disposal.<br>Granted, I see a trend wherein Verant is more and more distrustful of it's<br>Guides, but it could offer the chance to play a persistent NPC to Guides as<br>a role in addition to their Guides, much as they tried prior to most of the<br>Guide management quitting.  Perhaps anyone wishing to play a persistent<br>character could Guide for 10 hours and then spend 5-10 hours, whatever seems<br>a legitimate requirement, playing the NPC.  This would bring color,<br>continuity, and advanced interactions to the game.  As far as control, it<br>could be open to any Guide who had worked more than six months, or Verant<br>could even take a chance on players playing the roles, assigning them to<br>servers other than their own.<br><br>It's important that Verant step up this program.  "Sorry you missed it" is a<br>tired phrase for those of us who have been playing since retail and who have<br>seen maybe one, and certainly not historical, GM quest.  Let's see some<br>ingenuity coming out of Verant - the Hack and Slash is covered.<br><br>Oakgrove Fallingleaf

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem965505753,48885,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Grouping</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Lonnie E. Plott Jr.   (<a href="mailto:lonnieplottjr@hotmail.com" class="credit2">lonnieplottjr@hotmail.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
A lot of people get mad when they can't solo anymore. And you can always tell when they realize it won't work anymore. Depending on class and such, they say things like: "Not enough hit points anymore! Warriors got nerfed!" or "Root doesn't work it's too easy to resist!". Same goes for mana.<br><br>What people don't seem to realize is this game is specifically made for group adventure. Now I'm not saying it's impossible to solo: I managed to when I felt like it up to level 23. (By that time I just didn't want to, I have no idea whether you can or not past that.) It is just much more<br>difficult.<br><br>With a team behind/in front of you, particularly a well made one (lots of pets to avoid personal damage or healers and tanks), down time is a lot slower, without as much of a risk as getting ganged up on.<br><br>On the other hand, solo, you use your own health, own mana (if you're a<br>mage) which typically gets exhausted fighting one or two blues/greens, and<br>having another monster sneak up on you is an easy way to die. You have no<br>one watching your back!<br><br>With a quick eye, a good set of tactics, and knowledge of the zone line,<br>soloing can be very fruitful. BUT...You still may as well plan to die twice<br>as often.<br><br>The moral of this story: group up when possible, solo when absolutely<br>necessary.

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
