<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#8220;It&#8217;s a good plan I tell ya!&#8221; hastened Izzi, his shining purple robe shifting color ever so slightly to a soft metallic gray and then back to purple.  &#8220;It has to work.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The rest of the party sat around him staring in disbelief.  Izzi Fizzlethorpe, or so he called himself, was possibly the smartest Wizard Dreugh had ever met in his life.  He was a master of just about every skill known to mankind, (where he found the time and money to invest into these skills, the group never knew) and he used them all with good intent.  But mostly he was a Wizard, with enough of the arcane powers to roast many of the wandering nuisances of Norath in a single blast.  He was taller than most normal humans, an Erudite by race.  Most of the Erudites had shunned his abilities, claiming that he was unfocused on his studies and too preoccupied with the life of an adventurer rather than a scholar like the other members of his race.  Dreugh usually turned his nose up at the &#8220;Holier than thou&#8221; attitude of the Erudites, but Izzi was different.  More than once, he had been a formidable friend, and Dreugh was proud to be a member of his group.  He was a brilliant tactician, and everyone always placed their fate in his hands without question, knowing that he had thoroughly researched the situation at hand.  This time, however, Dreugh was quite skeptical&#8230; and judging from the look of his companions, they were not much further off from the same opinion as he.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As Dreugh surveyed his companions, he reflected the emotions radiating from the very essence of their being.  Goyr Holyblade: Paladin of great strength and virtue.  Dreugh had met Goyr for the first time when he had met Izzi, as they were traveling together when they decided to form their small union.  Goyr was just about the hairiest Dwarf that Dreugh had ever met.  His thick red hair seemed to grow from everywhere, and Dreugh could swear that he could even see hair coming through the Paladin&#8217;s armor sometimes.  Dreugh chuckled to himself over the thought and continued his assessment. Goyr had proven to be a most valuable team member, as well as a good friend. Barely reaching up to Dreugh&#8217;s chest, Goyr had to be the strongest Dwarf he had seen to date.  His melee skills were equaled by few for someone of his experience and his minor magical abilities granted to him from his Paladin gods had come in most useful when Dreugh had found himself spent from magical encounters.  Dreugh had also found a very important quality in the Dwarf: a good drinking companion.  Gods!  The little guy could drink several regular men under the table and go a-blazing into battle without a hindrance.  He really respected the Dwarf, and hoped to have many more encounters side by side with him.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh looked over to Gwynedd.  She was a dazzling sight to behold.  Possibly the most beautiful Wood Elf Dreugh had ever seen, (and he had seen SO many in those taverns in Kelethin where&#8230; um, that&#8217;s another story) this female Bard had the voice of golden honey.  Dreugh could swear that when she sang certain songs, he could actually fight better, feel stronger, or run faster.  Her face was sharp and fine, much like the Ykesha sword she carried at her hip.  Dreugh had learned all too quick how tough the slight Bard could be, and welcomed her strength as well as her beauty.  She was a recent, but welcome, addition to the party, and she currently stared dreamily into Izzi&#8217;s eyes.  Dreugh had suspected a love affair between the two from the start (not like they were hiding it) and was happy to see that his friend had found someone to share his heart with.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And then himself.  Dreugh Deadsbane.  He saw himself as a tall High Elf, taller than most and very lean with a pale white complexion and the albino type features that befit most of the High Elves of Felwithe.  Dreugh had chosen the Cleric&#8217;s path of life, or he should say Tunare had chosen him for the task.  Growing up in Felwithe, Dreugh never saw himself as a holy individual, but a vision of Tunare in a local church brought the all too swift conversion to faith and belief in the Mother of All.  Dreugh was hardly a fighter, even though he was a rather temperate and impetuous youth, and decided to place his energies into the spiritual and religious.  Soon, though, he would discover that like most Clerics, he had developed a distinct disliking for the Undead inhabitants of Norath. He then visited the head priest of his guild and asked to be placed on a pilgrimage to deliver Felwithe, and all of Norath, from the vile clutches of the Undead.  However, what he never realized he would find is that Norath was in need of further deliverance than the evil of Undead creatures.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;That&#8217;s when he met up with the other members of his group, and where he found himself right now, trying to figure out how he had gotten into such a mess.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;You know, Izz,&#8221; he said, &#8220;last time we tried this we nearly met Tunare a little earlier than I had planned to in life.&#8221;  Dreugh remembered all too well when Izzi had brought them to Permafrost and they attempted to do a little Ice Goblin hunting, and found that they were a little over matched for the tribes of goblins that seemed to spew from the mountains of North Antonica.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi shrugged in his ever-so-non-chalant manner and said, &#8220;Hey that wasn&#8217;t my fault.  How did I know there was a goblin breeding ground that close to where we were?&#8221;  As he spoke, his ever-present smirk came through and Dreugh couldn&#8217;t help but chuckle again.  No matter how many crazy schemes Izzi came up with, everything always seemed to go all right in the end.  He was, however, still a little skeptical about this latest scheme.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;His concern subsided slightly when Goyr blasted out, &#8220;The gods will grant us strength in our battle, as they always have before, and we will be the righteous victors this day.&#8221;  Then he flashed his big yellow-toothed grin and said, &#8220;Have ye no sense of adventure, Cleric-friend?  Izzi knows what he does, and will make sure we survive, like always.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh flashed his own grin in response, and retorted, &#8220;Goyr, I have no doubts of our friends&#8217; tactical and leadership abilities, since they are far better than mine.  But I think this time he has gone a bit far.  Just look at what he has in store for us!&#8221;  Dreugh gestured from the thicket in which they had been hiding and pointed straight at the biggest and ugliest monster he had ever seen.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi had promised him a good adventure this day, but he never said anything about a Cyclops!<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The beast was huge, almost as tall as a Hill Giant, and his features couldn&#8217;t have been more grotesque if they tried.  The monster&#8217;s teeth were long and spiked, and fit row by row in an oversized mouth.  It had one great big eye in the center of its face, and a forehead that made it look as if it may topple over from its immense size.  The rest of it&#8217;s body could be described as overweight, but with a strength that would uproot a tree, or tear apart a poor passing adventurer with a child&#8217;s ease.  When he was young he could remember the village elders claiming of such a monstrosity, but found it to be too unbelievable then.  He wished he had listened now.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;BAH!&#8221; came the reply from his hairy friend.  &#8220;Ye just watch what I do with me trusty Deepwater Harpoon when I get a hold of this beastie!&#8221;  Dreugh couldn&#8217;t help but smile.  He still remembered the day when he and Goyr had gotten a bit too drunk for their own good and started a fight with another party of adventurers.  Goyr had lifted the biggest member of their party (a barbarian warrior, no  less) off the ground by his, uh, sensitive area, and promised to shove the large harpoon up the warrior&#8217;s arse sideways if they didn&#8217;t depart swiftly and risk making him angry.  He was laughing through the entire ordeal.  Dreugh had though himself a dead man, when the warrior actually shuddered and passed out and the other members of his party actually ran, quickly.  Dreugh never underestimated the strength of a drunken Dwarf thereafter.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Just then, Gwynedd held up her hand in a gesture of silence and placed her finger to her lips to accent the need.  The Cyclops had been inspecting something on the ground, and now bent over to the pile which from where they were looked to be a mass of dirt.  Gwynedd gasped and paled, and Goyr cursed something under his breath in his guttural Dwarven language.  Izzi just stoically looked on and Dreugh edged forward to see what they had seen.  Only his battle-hardened stomach kept him from retching and nearly losing the lunch he consumed earlier.  The Cyclops was standing not over a pile of dirt, but a recently unfortunate adventurer who apparently was not lucky enough to defeat or avoid the beast.  But what made it even worse was what the monster was doing.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;He&#8217;s eating him..!&#8221; Dreugh gasped.  He didn&#8217;t realize he had spoke out loud until his companions shot him a quieting glare.  The Cyclops continued his meal undisturbed.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi broke from his watch and walked a few paces behind the group.  He then sat in a cross-legged position and removed a long dagger from his robe.  The athamae gleamed a blood red, and Izzi used it to begin drawing a circle on the ground.  Within the circle, he drew archaic symbols of power, while he removed a skin bag from his robe (Dreugh wondered where he found room in that thin robe for all those artifacts) and poured out several runes of bone with similar symbols on them.  As he drew the symbols, he began to chant in an ancient and forgotten language of magic.  He then finished his drawing and after replacing the items in his robe, placed his hands on his knees and continued his chant, eyes rolling back in his head to reveal only the whites.  Dreugh began to notice the nexus of power growing around his friend (something he noticed he could do when he first realized his own magical talent) and new it was time to prepare for the fight.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He turned to see his other companions had gotten the hint as well.  Goyr had stuck his harpoon point down into the dirt and knelt on one knee in front of it, muttering something in an Old Dwarven tongue.  Dreugh&#8217;s Dwarven was poor, but he managed to make out words like &#8220;strength&#8221; and &#8220;victory&#8221;, along with other prayers to the Paladin god he worshiped.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gwynedd was leaning against a tree, quietly tuning her mandolin, almost as much a weapon as her sword.  She compared the notes coming from the stringed instrument to the perfect notes she sang.  Dreugh felt his heart soar and his body relax at the notes she played, and she hadn&#8217;t even started playing a melody yet.  The Bard glanced and noticed him staring.  She offered a grin and a wink, and went back to work on tuning.  Dreugh couldn&#8217;t help but grin like a little boy.  Izzi was a lucky man.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He then decided to make some preparations of his own.  He removed the shield he carried at his back.  It gleamed iridescent silver, and had a dull gray cross painted in the center.  Ever since he had acquired the shield, he had noticed that his mana abilities had increased dramatically, giving him the ability to cast longer and more spells.  He then removed the mace hanging from his belt loop.  The mace was a deep enameled black color, unnaturally so.  It was an effective weapon in his adventures, and these days felt almost like an extension of his own arm.  He then knelt down on both knees and spread his arms wide and to his side.  He looked up into the trees and sky, and down to the earth and land.  He said his own silent prayer to Tunare in Elder Elvish, using the more proper syntax to address his deity.  A cascading light from above the trees beamed down on him, gleaming off of his freshly polished armor and created a splendid rainbow that Dreugh felt he could ride into battle on.  He could feel the sudden rush of power in the blessing that soon followed and his eyes opened wide.  He knew that this day Tunare would be by their side in the fight.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Ahem,&#8221; came the beckon from his side.  Dreugh then looked to each of his party members as they stood beside him cross-armed and waiting.  How long had he been there?  He quickly stood and retrieved his weapons.  &#8220;Are you ready now, Sir Cleric?&#8221; came the whimsical question from Izzi.  &#8220;Because we&#8217;ve got a job to do.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh smiled and replied, &#8220;Almost.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He placed his hands in front of himself and began to chant.  He wove his hands in a delicate pattern, left and right, up and down, and completed the spell.  He felt the rush of extra energy surge into his body, adding to his strength and vitality.  He then cast a spell of magical armor to protect himself for physical attack.  With his personal protective barriers completed, he repeated the spells for each of his companions and watched their appreciative nods as each received the castings.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi then beckoned the group back to their original spot where the Cyclops was about half way through his adventurer lunch.  Somehow the beast looked bigger than before, as if he had somehow grown in a manner of minutes.  Dreugh then noticed for the first time that the Cyclops had a giant sword at his hip.  The sword looked as if it could easily cleave his body in two, as a kitchen knife would a tomato.  Izzi motioned the group closer and they huddled around him to listen to the plan.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Okay,&#8221; he started.  &#8220;This is what we&#8217;ll do.  Goyr, you run point and take the beast head on, keep his attention from me long enough to cast some spells.  I&#8217;m afraid you&#8217;ll have to take most of the hits in the beginning.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Goyr grinned his big yellow-toothed grin and belted, &#8220;Bah!  He won&#8217;t know what hit &#8216;em!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi smiled his own little smile, and replied, &#8220;Good.  Now Dreugh, I need you to stay back a bit and watch our vitality.  You will need to heal us if you can.  If the battle looks to be going well, you&#8217;re more than welcome to throw one of those little Cleric attack spells.  But I prefer you don&#8217;t.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh knew this speech pretty well, for Izzi used it just about every time they went into battle.  Dreugh&#8217;s response was a curt nod and a, &#8220;Will do,&#8221; before Izzi turned his attention over to the next party member.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And when he did, Gwynedd smiled her most disarming smile (Gods!  How he wished she wouldn&#8217;t DO that!).  Izzi then whispered, &#8220;Now, Love.  As much as I would just love to tell you to sit back, sing and look pretty, I cannot.  I am afraid I need your skills at the blade as well.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Her smile then became a wicked grin as she punched Izzi in the shoulder.  The blow took him off guard and he fell back, a mildly defeated look on his face that read, &#8220;What was that for?&#8221;  She then retorted, &#8220;Am I not a member of this party also?  I can hack it with the best of you, and have before.  Do not treat me as some weak child or unable woman.&#8221;  And with that she offered hand to Izzi and he grasped it and rose.  He rubbed his shoulder grinning and Dreugh was once again reminded that her small exterior was no reflection of the warrior spirit that dwelled within her.  Just to show that she wasn&#8217;t angry, she reached over and planted a big kiss on Izzi&#8217;s lips.  Dreugh watched the two melt into each other, and envied the relationship that was steadily growing between them.  He glanced at Goyr who seemed to be admiring some rocks in the corner of the forest.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The two separated and regained their composure.  Izzi then addressed the group once more.  &#8220;Now, if we&#8217;re ready, let&#8217;s go.&#8221;  He moved to the edge of the open area that the Cyclops inhabited and signaled a halt.  He turned to the group and mouthed, &#8220;On three.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh readied himself, mentally checking his equipment and weapons.  This was the part of adventuring that was the least and most fun at the same time.  The thrill of battle and driving back the enemy for the goodness of the land was something he was born to do.  However, getting hurt in the process was something he did not relish at all.  In fact, he down right detested it.  Such was the price to pay to fulfill his destiny.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi held up his index finger to represent the number one.  He currently had his gaze locked on the Cyclops and concentrated on the task at hand.  Dreugh felt the pit of his stomach churn like someone just dropped him from the top of the highest tree in Kelethin and he was watching the floor of the great forest of Greater Faydark plunge towards him.  It was mildly disconcerting, but Dreugh managed to place his fears in the back of his mind long enough to realize that his knuckles were turning white from gripping his mace.  He relaxed his grip, and his body and waited for the next step.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi held up two fingers and Dreugh almost felt a rekindled wave of nausea.  He thought he might pass out from the mental ordeal, but he managed to quell his fears once again and concentrate more at the task at hand.  But before he could realize what was going on, or even before Izzi signaled for three, Dreugh noticed a small, hairy figure in bronzed armor running across the open field screaming a bloodthirsty war cry.  Dreugh looked to his left where the Dwarf was standing at his side a second ago and, sure enough, he was no longer standing there.  &#8220;For the glory of Kaladim!&#8221; Bellowed the Dwarf, and he spat other things in his guttural language before running down on the still unsuspecting Cyclops.  He was waving his Deepwater Harpoon in the air as his little legs ran him towards his target.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh and the rest of his group moaned and ran after their companion.  They should have known that their impatient little friend would try something like this.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Goyr was almost upon the beast when it looked up from its meal unconcerned (for what stupid creature dare attack a Cyclops alone?) and managed to actually duck out of the intended deathblow aimed at its oversized single eye.  Goyr stumbled from the force of his own momentum and the unfortunate miss and almost fell over.  The Cyclops stood to its full height and roared its challenge at the Paladin, unaware that the rest of the party was behind him.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh looked to his right and saw that Izzi was already beginning his first spell, a blue-gray nimbus of power surrounded his hands and was growing wider and wider.  Gwynedd was singing a battle chant that Dreugh could already feel grant him strength to his muscles.  Goyr was recovering from his miss, but the Cyclops was already drawing his massive sword from the scabbard.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh quickly mouthed the words to a minor stun spell and aimed it at the Cyclops.  He was amazed when he was thrown back a few steps and noticed the creature had some sort of natural magical immunity to his spell.  Dreugh noticed Izzi scowl in disappointment at the failed attempt, even though he was in the middle of his own casting.  He could almost hear the disapproving scold from his friend, &#8220;I said heal, damn you!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;But what he didn&#8217;t notice is that the Cyclops had stopped his advance slightly on Goyr to glance at Dreugh long enough for him to recover from his stumble and ready for battle.  Dreugh grinned at the not-so-failed attempt at a distraction and saw Gwynedd sneak behind the monster and slice at it&#8217;s Achilles tendon.  The Cyclops threw its hands up in a bellow of pain and anger and turned his attention towards the Bard.  She was already retreating and just barely managed to avoid a crushing deathblow from the beast&#8217;s fist.  It was incredibly fast for a creature so large, but not fast enough to catch the wily Bard.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Just then, Izzi managed to get off his spell, and what a spell it was!  Dreugh could feel the blast streak by at impossible speed and catch the beast square in the chest.  He was not so lucky to resist the spell this time, and actually toppled back a few steps from the impact.  The beast howled in rage and fury and Dreugh felt his teeth chatter from the hatred it the scream.  It was hurt from the blow, and that only seemed to fuel its desire to kill ever more.  It began an advance on Izzi, its massive sword held over its head meant to cleave the Wizard in twain.  Izzi had already begun his second spell.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Just then, Goyr took his Harpoon and hefted it like a javelin.  He wound up way back and heaved it at the Cyclops.  It struck the beast square in the back below the neckline on its shoulder blade.  It looked as though a toothpick had hit it, but the shaft sank deep and managed to get another bellow of pain from the monster.  It never stopped its advance on the Wizard.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh needed to think fast.  He summoned the forces of his mana store and shaped them into a smiting blast, aimed at the head of the beast.  The blast stuck home, but only managed to do minimal damage to the Cyclops, and never seemed to stop its advance.  The Wizard was done for.  He would never finish that spell before the Cyclops split him down the middle.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;HEY, UGLY!&#8221;  came the sudden taunt from behind the beast.  Dreugh was dumbfounded when the beast actually stopped and he looked around to see where the taunt came from.  &#8220;Yeah, I&#8217;m talkin&#8217; to you, you overstuffed bag of dragon dung!&#8221;  The beast whirled around and stared at his newest target.  Goyr stood in the center of the clearing with an arrow knocked in his bow, aimed for the upper portion of the beast&#8217;s torso.  &#8220;You know, if I was you, I&#8217;d cut me own ugly head off to spare meself the pain of having to look at such a hideous creature.&#8221;  Dreugh was amazed at the bravery that exuded from the Dwarf.  But he also remembered something else he was once told.  The Cyclops understood Common Tongue, so Goyr&#8217;s taunts were quite effective in distracting the beast.  It set off again, after the Dwarf, its fury renewed and its bloodlust rekindled.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Goyr let loose the arrow he had knocked and it went straight and true to its intended target: the Cyclops&#8217; eye.  But somehow, the beast once again showed its amazing speed and was able to deflect the arrow with its massive hand as if swatting a fly.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Goyr threw down his bow and pulled free his Crystalline Sword and shield.  The sword was as clear as the daylight and looked like it was made of glass.  But Dreugh knew that the enchantments laid upon the blade made it stronger than any normal metal.  Goyr threw his hands up and roared his challenge at the mighty beast.  He was actually going to challenge the thing toe to toe!  He couldn&#8217;t even be much larger than the beast&#8217;s foot, and yet he stood fast and awaited his opponent.  A brave fool indeed.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In his momentary panic, Dreugh lacked the ability to think up a spell that would distract the beast, and watched as it lumbered closer and closer to its intended victim.  Goyr was grinning so big that he could actually see the yellow-toothed grin from where he was standing.  Izzi finally managed to get off his second spell, which was a blazing spiral of fire that connected with the Cyclops&#8217; backside and set him on fire.  Aside from a small flinch, the beast never stopped its advance.  Gwynedd managed to get in close and take another slice at its leg, but this time it bounced off harmlessly as the beast&#8217;s natural skin gave it protection from such things.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh shot off another spell of his own, which did surprisingly more damage than the first, but still not enough to slow the beast&#8217;s advance.  Once again, one of his friends looked as though he may be on the brink of death.  The Cyclops heaved its mighty sword in the air and swung down upon Goyr.  He managed to just barely avoid the blow and take a swipe of his own.  The Crystalline Sword sunk deep into the leg of the Cyclops, and Goyr pulled it free just as quickly with a triumphant &#8220;HA!&#8221;, and a black-red blood fountain erupted from the beast&#8217;s leg.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Just then the Cyclops brought down its other arm and dealt a crushing blow, which caught Goyr across the back and sent him flying across the field.  &#8220;NOOO!!&#8221; screamed all three remaining companions in unison.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi somehow managed to get off another spell with a quickness Dreugh had never seen him do.  A pillar of ice shot towards the Cyclops and caught him in the side.  The monster stammered and managed to somehow stand and make his slow advance on Izzi.  His howling rage was now gone and he advanced slowly on the remaining three members.  Izzi shot a quick but concerned glance at Dreugh and with that look he communicated volumes.  <I>You need to help Goyr, now!</I><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi began to prepare another spell, and Gwynedd was at his side, sword drawn and panting.  &#8220;GO!&#8221; she screamed.  &#8220;I will stay with him.  Go help the Paladin!&#8221;  Her words were urgent, but he knew that she was right.  He could feel Goyr&#8217;s life essence draining from him at this very instant.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Somehow, Dreugh managed to get around the beast and make it to his friends&#8217; side.  He was faced down in a heap of bones, and after careful prodding, Dreugh had found that several bones were broken, including his spine and neck.  That always meant death.  Panic-stricken, Dreugh went against all his medical knowledge and turned his companion over on his back to look into his face.  He called forth the forces of healing that he had used so many times before and poured energy &#8211; a lot of his energy &#8211; into his downed friend.  Goyr convulsed, his body reacting to the healing spell, and many of his visible cuts had healed and most of his broken bones had mended.  He sucked in a ragged breath of air and began breathing, but his strength was very low.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Goyr reached up to grab Dreugh&#8217;s tunic in his small, but hairy, fist and he managed to speak.  &#8220;No time&#8230; for that now, Cleric-friend,&#8221; and his eyes fluttered, but he remained conscious.  &#8220;Go help&#8230; Izzi and Gwynedd.&#8221;  His breathing was heavy and labored, and he sounded as if he may not make it still.  Dreugh turned to look at the battle going on.  The other two party members had managed to score many cuts on the legs of the Cyclops, and it was staggering now.  Dreugh saw Izzi&#8217;s hands wave and another blot of energy exploded across the chest of the beast.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With one last breath, Goyr stammered, &#8220;I&#8217;ll be&#8230; fine&#8230; go&#8230; help them,&#8221; and he began to cough up some blood.  Dreugh placed his friend&#8217;s head on the ground gently (when did he place it in his hands?) and went to his companions to help finish off the beast.  This would end, now.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh picked up his mace and shield and stared up at the now limping Cyclops.  Blood still poured from the open wound on its leg.  It appeared that Goyr might have opened a main artery in the beast&#8217;s leg and he was bleeding to death.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With renewed faith, Dreugh suppressed all of his fears and called upon the forces of Holy Might, a spell known to very few Clerics, but one that would give him enough time to do what he needed.  The spell should stun the Cyclops, as well as do some injury in the process, which should further weaken him.  Dreugh started to draw the power within himself, feel the mana swirl through him, he channeled much more energy into the spell than he normally did, enough to render an Ogre immobile for minutes, and held it with in himself.  He drew upon the power, and focused it at the head of the Cyclops.  It must hit the head, or this will be all for naught.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The powerful blast erupted from him with such fury, he barely contained it, and it struck the Cyclops directly in the head.  The beast shuddered once, and toppled over backwards.  Dreugh managed to stay conscious long enough to see Gwynedd jam her sword deep into the eye of the Cyclops and into its brain.  Dreugh smiled as he felt the life essence drain away from the Cyclops, just before he fell into blackness&#8230;<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh woke later &#8211; he didn&#8217;t know how much later &#8211; to stare straight up into Gwynedd&#8217;s lovely eyes.  If he didn&#8217;t respect and cherish his friendship with Izzi so much, he may try to steal the lovely Bard from under his nose.  Dreugh smiled as she caressed his cheek and heard her say, &#8220;He&#8217;s awake.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi stood next to her, his face looked sunken in, as if he had been using magic for hours.  His smile said that he was all right, and Dreugh managed to believe that sometimes-deceiving smile.  That&#8217;s when he remembered.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Goyr?&#8221; he managed to choke out.  His throat felt dry like he hadn&#8217;t had a drink in weeks.  Gwynedd handed him a drink, water, to his disappointment, but he still drank all of it greedily and felt his strength returning.  He suddenly noticed he was inside somewhere, but where?<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi noticed his puzzled look and said, &#8220;We&#8217;re in Kaladim.  I felt it best for Goyr&#8217;s body to be returned to his family for proper burial.&#8221;  His look was very sad and he noticed a tear forming in his eye.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Burial?  Kaladim?  NO!  He was alive.  Dreugh had seen him healed, and he had promised he was okay.  He should have known not to trust the little Dwarf.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;The Healers did all they could, but he did not survive,&#8221; Izzi went on.  &#8220;They&#8217;re a little surprised to see that you did as well.  Said that blast should have killed you.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No.  NO!  He can&#8217;t be dead.  He was alive. Dreugh saw it, saw it with his own eyes. And he promised he was all right.  He promised!<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi caught the look of confusion in Dreugh&#8217;s face and placed a hand on his shoulder.  &#8220;You did all you could,&#8221; he comforted.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Did he?  Was there more that he could do?  He had heard the Clerics of higher order speak of the Talent in one to be able to revive the dead, but he never thought it possible.  He had also thought there was no such thing as a Cyclops yesterday, as well.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Take me to him,&#8221; he commanded.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The other two looked at each other and sighed.  &#8220;Dreugh,&#8221; Izzi started, &#8220;there&#8217;s nothing more you can do.  He is gone from this realm on to the next.  He will be missed by many.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I said take me to him!&#8221;  The snap was a bit more than he expected, but there wasn&#8217;t much time.  He needed to see Goyr fast.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;All right, my friend.  I will take you to him.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They went through a series of corridors in Kaladim.  Dreugh marveled at the inner workings of the Dwarven City.  It looked completely hand carved, intricately designed and fortified.  The Dwarves were reputed stone masons and miners, and the tunnels showed just that.  Izzi and Dreugh had to squat just a little to fit in the tunnels, since they were meant for the height of Dwarves.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They came upon an open area where in the middle Dreugh could see many Dwarves huddled around what seemed to be a coffin of sorts.  Goyr was laid out on top, covered in a sheer cloth.  Many of what looked to be family and friends of the Dwarf saw them enter.  Some looked away in shame, others stared straight into his eyes as if to ask, &#8220;Couldn&#8217;t you do something?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh strode towards the corpse of his friend and was stopped with a stubby, hairy hand in the gut.  &#8220;Who bade ye enter to the sacred ceremony?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh looked down into the eyes of what could have been Goyr&#8217;s twin if Goyr were several years older.  A relative perhaps? Maybe his father?<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Please,&#8221; he begged with the Dwarf.  &#8220;Please I must help him.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Dwarf stared him straight in the face and accused, &#8220;Are ye the one that travels with those who brought me boy back?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;His father then.  This would be tough.  Dreugh knew Dwarves to be a mostly superstitious lot, feeling no one should tamper with the dead.  They saw it as bordering Necromancy.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Please, I must help him.  There isn&#8217;t time for arguing.  Any longer and it could be too late!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Don&#8217;t ya think it is too late enough, Laddie?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Please,&#8221; was all he said in return.  He looked into the eyes of the older Dwarf and tried to convey his true meaning.  He needed to convince him that he was here to help, not to shame or dishonor the family name.  He wanted to help his friend.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The old Dwarf must have seen something in Dreugh&#8217;s eyes, because his hardened stare softened and looked deep within his soul.  &#8220;All righty, Cleric-friend,&#8221; Dreugh&#8217;s heart tugged at the mention of his familiar name given by Goyr.  &#8220;But be ye warned.  Ye do one thing to defile me boy, and I&#8217;ll tear ya limb from limb meself!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh knew he was serious, and his only response was a nod.  The old Dwarf stepped aside and motioned for the others &#8211; who had been watching intently &#8211; to move aside.  They parted and Dreugh stepped through the crowd and up to the pyre that was constructed for his friend.  He barely contained a sob and managed to approach the covered corpse of his friend.  He pulled back the sheer coving and looked at his friend&#8217;s face.  None of that daredevil spirit or the fire of life was anywhere to be found within him, but there was&#8230; something.  He couldn&#8217;t say what, but he had never examined a corpse before, and there was something there that felt as if he could almost see it.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Dreugh?&#8221; came the question from Izzi.  The single word spoke countless questions.  But he looked into the face of Wizard he called his friend and gave a look that said, &#8220;I must.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Izzi started to open his mouth, but changed his mind.  Gwynedd was at his side and wrapped her arm around his waist and beckoned him to back away.  A tear dropped from Izzi&#8217;s eye, and just then Dreugh realized what Izzi was so concerned about.  Sometimes he forgot that Goyr and Izzi had known each other from the beginning.  Their adventures had come before Dreugh had joined the group.  Izzi wasn&#8217;t showing concern that he would fail.  He was giving his support to succeed.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Once again, Dreugh found himself pushing back his own fears and inhibitions.  He looked deep within the lifeless body of Goyr.  He searched deep within the empty caverns of the Dwarf&#8217;s soul.  He came up on countless dead ends, and seemed as though he would never locate the source of the spark that was slowly fading away.  Panic seeped into his soul again and he closed his eyes.  He breathed in and out, in and out.  He regulated his own heartbeat, slowed it to a more natural pulse from the racing beat it had taken on.  He sought once again into the empty soul that was before him and found that something again, this time it was growing much more faint.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh had to act fast.  He wove the colors of life and death in his mind, saw the patterns of the cosmos come to him in his need.  He reached his arms out and threw his head back.  Light cascaded from somewhere above him, he could not tell where.  The heat from the light threatened to burn, and yet protected him from all.  He gathered the power within himself, fed it to the patterns in his mind.  He wove the delicate threads into place and they seemed to fall into place so naturally.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;But he was tired, so very tired.  His ordeal with the Cyclops had left him spent, magically and physically, and he felt the power draining from his body.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<I>Tunare</I>, he thought into the cosmos. <I>Tunare, I beg thee, Mother to All.  Grant me the strength to do what I must! </I><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;What Dreugh received in response was more than he expected.  The light intensified, and the power rushed into him like a dam being opened.  He had never felt so much power before in his life!  Tunare was with him, granting him the strength and the power as he had asked.  He must not fail now.  He searched with his mind once again deep within the empty shell of his friend and found the almost depleted life spark.  Desperately, he channeled the energy into it.  He focused his entire existence into it. He was the flow, the power.  He needed to save his friend.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;After countless moments of time, he felt the spark waver and twitch.  YES!  He thought.  Come on Goyr, you can do it!<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was then that he heard the voice in his head.  Whether it was his own, Tunare&#8217;s, or Goyr&#8217;s, he did not know, but the voice responded, No, YOU can do it.  Dreugh continued to feed the power into the web he had woven - continued to feed the now growing spark of energy that was Goyr&#8217;s life force.  He could swear that he felt Goyr twitch in his grasp, (when did he place his head in his hands again?) and opened his eyes to see Goyr&#8217;s fingers twitch, then his leg.  He fed more and more of the power into the spark in his mind, and it glowed so bright that he could barely stand it any more.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dreugh fed all the rest of the spell energy into the spark, until it threatened to blind his magical sight, and Goyr sucked in a ragged, but strong gust of air.  He felt, rather than heard the gasps come from the room full of Dwarves watching this display.  He might gasp if he was watching too.  Two, three more breaths, and he started to breath normally.  Goyr&#8217;s eyes opened wide, as if in shock, and he leapt up from the table.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;What in Bloody Hell&#8217;s goin&#8217; on here?&#8221; Goyr questioned wearily, and that was the last thing Dreugh heard before he collapsed into a heap and let the darkness wash over him again.<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Hours, days, maybe even weeks later - he didn&#8217;t know - he woke again.  It was dark in the room, a small candle lit on the dresser was the only light Dreugh could see, and that was blurry enough.  He tried to wipe the crust from his eyes, and found that his arms were leaden.  He felt as weak as a newborn kitten.  After a few minutes, he managed to wipe away most of the sleep from his eyes, and prop himself up on one arm.  He surveyed the room, and found it to be the same room he was in the first time, only he was alone this time.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Somewhere, somehow, he managed to find the strength to sit up and drink from the pitcher on the dresser next to the bed.  More water, (What he wouldn&#8217;t do for good ale right now!) but it helped to subside the massive headache he didn&#8217;t realize he had.  There was also some meat and bread on a plate next to the pitcher, and he managed to eat all of the food before lying back down.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;When he woke again, (when did he fall asleep?) it was much later.  He could tell because the candle had burned down so low and someone had been in to replace the food and water without rousing him.  He sat up, which was much easier this time, and managed to get dressed and go out of the room.  After stepping out into a well-lit area and being temporarily blinded, he managed to clear his sight and find the room where his friends had been eating dinner.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;When he entered the room he saw them turn around and bound from the table.  Izzi and Gwynedd reached him first and prodded him with a million questions: Was he all right?  How did he feel?  Will he be able to duplicate the spell?  (That was Izzi.  Always looking to have the impossible.)  And then he heard it.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;If you two would kindly step aside and let me Cleric-friend have an ale, we could be over and done with this already!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They stepped back to reveal Goyr at the table eating a big plate of some meat and guzzling the biggest tankard of ale he&#8217;d ever seen.  He put the tankard down and let out a satisfying &#8220;aahhhh&#8221; along with a cavern-echoing belch.  &#8220;Well, Dreugh?&#8221; he asked.  &#8220;Ye gonna sit there and gawk, or ye gonna share some of me ale before I finish it all?&#8221;  And then he flashed a yellow-toothed grin so large that Dreugh though he might split his face.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The four stood around the table together and toasted to their adventures, and the many more to come.<br>

