From the responses to the last editorial, I can see that there is a great<br>deal of interest in this particular topic.  I think a couple of points<br>needs to be elaborated, however, so I am taking another stab at this.<br><br>Granted, not having a base of operations on a harsh continent like Kunark<br>must really make some players angry, especially after working through a<br>long dungeon crawl only to return to a city in which you formerly had<br>favored citizen status and end up slaughtered.  It would make me angry.  On<br>the other hand, much of EQ is trial by fire, and it's meant to be that way.<br> <br><br>Faction was put in the game to add an element hard to find in online games<br>- a complex system of cause and effect to take the game to a different<br>level.  In the case of the Kunark factions for evil races, you have to make<br>a choice, and that choice is which of the options appeals most - the fort<br>or the dungeon?  For those who have chosen the dungeon and have no place to<br>sell or rest, that's what wizard teleports are for, so you can get back to<br>the mainland and take care of business.<br><br>I am sure that some will now argue how they should not have to rely on<br>another class to simply buy or sell.  In truth, however, that's part of why<br>we choose classes.  We do have to rely on the other classes in situations<br>where we cannot take care of a specific situation ourselves.<br><br>I believe in the character development facet of of EQ - however, I don't<br>believe you have to have access to every area of the game.  That's why you<br>choose evil or good races, specific classes and make faction decisions. <br>That sets EQ apart from the normal online games.<br><br>Oakgrove Fallingleaf

