<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The Bottom Line</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Shadoe  (<a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault Columnist</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
It seems to me that lately there has been so much more angst over EverQuest by the player base at large.  There seems to be a lot more people griping about something-or-other that happens to be wrong with the game who are no longer content with merely threatening to cancel their EQ accounts, but who actually <I>are</I> leaving the game purportedly forever.  Issues such as guide/GM abuse, Verant's elusive and indefinable Vision(tm) that's more a vehicle of convenience for them than anything, the ever-mutating game mechanics that are altered at the drop of a hat in the name of an "evolving world," player/item wipes taking place on the Test Server, sporadic (but no less frustrating) bugs that Verant tends to hold in skepticism until enough players complain that it becomes unavoidable months later, innumerable broken quests that make you spend hours of your time to complete only to be snuffed in the end, patches that seemingly break more things than they repair, uber-guilds who monopolize adventure areas in clear defiance of the loudly touted (but often unenforceable) Play Nice Policies... need I go on?<P>In short, the players are forming the impression that Verant Interactive doesn't care about them.  Rightly or wrongly, and for some unfathomable reason, Verant has allowed themselves to be viewed as "the Enemy" by a great number of players who try so desperately hard to enjoy their product.  And let's not mince words here, even irate players who leave the game in a huff <I>want</I> to enjoy EverQuest.  It's a disappointment for both parties when a player decides that ten dollars per month is too much to pay for the alleged "hassle" of adventuring in Norrath.  Not only is Verant out one more monthly payment, but the player is also bereft of something they were once very enthusiastic about.<P>On one side of the equation, it is something Verant has had to form a necessarily thick skin over.  You can't please all of the people all of the time, and that holds absurdly true when catering to an active player base in excess of 250,000 people.  On the other side of the equation, we have a very disgruntled person who sees Verant Interactive as the collective Anti-Christ of the twenty-first century.<P>The truth of that standpoint is subjective.  It makes no sense that a company whose life's blood flows from its customers (is there any other kind of company?) would so callously hold them in the same regard as sheep.  A spurned customer base is a short-lived customer base, and hence the same can be said for the business.  So, I think it's safe to say that Verant, in fact, <I>does</I> care for its players as a community.  Which begs the residual question: Do they care for their players as individuals?  Should they?<P>At ten dollars a month, is one individual's enjoyment of the game worthy of attention?  The bottom line says that a dissatisfied player has one of two choices - to leave the game or to stay.  If they decide to stay, then so much the better - whether or not they're enjoying themselves to the fullest potential is irrelevant.  If they decide to leave, then it's a loss of ten out of over two-and-a-half million dollars revenue per month.  When faced with those numbers, what would your answer be?<P>Speaking candidly, my answer would be to sell out and take one month's income with me to the Bahamas where I can live the rest of my natural life lying in the sun on a warm beach sipping pina coladas.  No, I'm not proud of that, but there you go.  I also know I wouldn't be lonely on that beach if every other EQ player had the same option.<P>If you can honestly say otherwise, then I invite you to cast the first stone.  My personal opinion is that there is no mortal alive on this planet who could possibly care for a quarter of a million individuals, making sure each and every player is happy and content in the trouble-free, paradisiacal dream world we all wish Norrath could be.  Adding the numbers into the mix, I doubt many would feel motivated to try.<P>So what happens?  Players feel put upon.  Players feel abandoned for the ten dollars they cough up every month.  Players become embittered when told that's all their opinions are worth, and many leave the game because of it, defying the 249,999 people remaining to follow suit.  Capitalism at its finest.<P>But what happens when you're sitting on what is widely considered to be the best massively multiplayer game in town?  (Albeit arguably.)  With slim pickings as to where to go, a great deal of players will choose to remain until something better comes along.  People start to think that, considering their limited options, maybe things aren't so bad after all.  At least, this is what they think until the next game is introduced, making the current game look like an incarnation of massively multiplayer Pong.  Again, capitalism at its finest.<P>People said the same thing about Ultima Online before it had any competition.  I know - I was one of them.  I also think that EverQuest is a far superior game to Ultima Online, cited problems and all.  Has it hurt Origin Systems that every month over 250,000 people pay Verant Interactive ten dollars to agree with me?  <P>I may read their signals wrong, but Origin doesn't seem too worried.  They don't seem even the slightest bit uncomfortable.  The massively multiplayer market has been growing beyond all belief.  Quite simply, there's financial room in the playground for more game companies to play - a <I>lot</I> more.<P>It will take time for the market to veer off and level out, my friends.  The Internet is young, and massively multiplayer gaming is even younger.  Given enough time, the number of people who play massively multiplayer games will begin to stabilize.  By that time there will be more options for online games to play than Hillary Clinton has lobbyists.  Not only will monthly prices drop, but you will be able to pick and choose the game that best suits <I>your</I> play style.  Existing game companies like Verant and Origin will have to start actually competing for your business.  They will be forced to take a serious look at how they treat their individual customers, because if they fail to satisfy their players, there will be a hundred other companies out there who will.  Suddenly the bottom line begins to <I>serve</I> the player's individual liberties - not strike against them.<P>If you don't believe me, then believe this... it's already happening.  Games like <A HREF="http://vampirevault.ign.com/">Vampire: The Masquerade</A> and <A HREF="http://nwvault.ign.com/">NeverWinter Nights</A> are already starting to elbow their way into homes.  Though technically not massively multiplayer games (though if some philanthropist invested in some serious hardware, they could be), I see them as a profound threat to the genre's profitability.<P>Think about it... imagine being able to play EverQuest <I>your</I> way, without being held hostage by Verant's Vision(tm).  Imagine being given the liberty to make Norrath in your image where you make up the rules of how the game should be played, where it makes sense that a bard can use a bow, or a warrior can use a special crystal given to him by a kind dragon to teleport home.  Imagine a world that is tailored to your ideals as a player, where you and the Dungeon Master see eye to eye on 95% of all play issues.  Imagine taking comfort in knowing that if any jerk comes along who openly shuns those ideals, that they can be swept away on a whim because they're not paying customers who claim a right to play it as they see fit.  Imagine being able to choose from <I>thousands</I> of Norraths to play in, making such "abuse" practically meaningless for yourself.<P>Considering all these things, I'm having a tough time mentally justifying ten dollars a month to play in a static world where a conglomerate of employees dictate how I am to advance my characters.  I much prefer the idea that I can form a one-on-one repertoire with the powers that be, so I can essentially find my own path as I go through my adventures.  If things turn sour on that server, I exit and explore elsewhere or even create a world of my own.  <P>Somehow I think I'm not the only one who finds this particular vision far more palatable than any massively multiplayer game could conceive.  Sooner or later, people will realize how much more freedom they can have for <I>no</I> monthly fee.  The only thing missing is thousands of players to interact with.  It's up to you to decide if that's a bad thing or not.<P>Well, contrary to appearances, I didn't mean for this to turn into an anti-EverQuest / anti-Verant / anti-massively multiplayer article.  I'm still an avid fan of the game, even if I do get cheesed off at some of the cavalier things Verant says and does from time to time.  It helps that I've chosen to roleplay characters that remain, for the most part, unconcerned about their level (at least, until it becomes convenient to).  If the rigors of camping and farming in EverQuest start grating on your nerves, I'd recommend giving it a try before canceling your account.  It can open a lot of unexpected doors for finding enjoyment and fulfillment in Norrath.  <P>It did for me.<P>- &lt;Shadoe&gt;

