<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Heart's Journey, Part 2</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Boladorn Stormsong  (<a href="mailto:" class="credit2"></a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.lostorder.com/msgboards/conclave" class="credit2">The Conclave</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
A chill wind blew from the ice covered mountains as the distant thud of giant footfalls echoed through the valley. At the moss covered ruins swirls of light materialized in the air as three adventurers came into view. <br><br>Boladorn still clasped Kahlani&#8217;s hand as the two steadied themselves from their journey. They took stock of themselves and began their journey eastward to the elven outpost in Firiona Vie. The trip was not without peril as both the bard and Paladin were cut down along the way&#8230; the victim of the insidious half dark elf, half spider creatures that infested the dreadlands. <br><br>Once their possessions had been recovered the trio continued their journey and arrived in Firiona Vie with little additional trouble. <br><br>After gathering supplies and catching their breath for a moment, the three continued their journey through the lands, passing through the Lake of Ill Omens then on to The Frontier Mountains. An elven scout brought word to the three that their presence was required in Overthere. They quickly made their way through the pass to Overthere. <br><br>Boladorn found signs of their passing and tracked the members of Cestus Dei to a ruined tower in the eastern portion of the zone. <br><br>"Hail and well met Cestus Dei" greeted the bard. The members present turned and greeted the bard as he arrived. The three new arrivals were greeted with slaps on backs and hugs all around as word had arrived before them of their falling in the dreadlands. "Quite the selfless act bard, our thanks to you for bringing Kahlani to us, we are in your debt kind sir" said Apostate the cleric of Cestus Dei. <br><br>Boladorn looked at the ground and shrugged off the compliment. "I know the lay of the lands well and I was headed this direction anyway, &#8216;twas my pleasure to escort such pleasant company as her" he replied. <br><br>Kahlani cleared her throat and approached Boladorn, a mischievous grin on her face. She drew her sword and came closer to Boladorn "Please kneel a moment if thou wouldst" she asked. Boladorn removed his helm and knelt at her feet. "For your acts of bravery and the selfless act of guiding me through the perils these lands are infested with I knight thee Boladorn, True Knight of Kahlani" she said solemnly. <br><br>Boladorn drew a deep breath and lowered his gaze to hide the blush that was spreading across his cheeks. He accepted the knighting and rose to his feet. For a while the group caught each other up on recent news while trying to clear the ancient ruins of the Sarnaks that infested them. After some time word came of Wurms wandering the burning wood and the decision was made to investigate. The group traveled to the burning wood without incident. <br><br>As the group prepared themselves for the coming hunt Boladorn studied the paladin as she sat in meditation. "What a wondrous woman she be" he thought to himself. "Could it be that there is more here than what I have seen so far, Could it be that I have in some way found a place in her heart?" he asked himself. <br><br>She looked up from her prayers and saw him watching her. She did not want to embarrass him so did not acknowledge his staring eyes. "What luck to find one such as he! One that would act so honorably, so selfless to guide a lost soul across these blasted lands for nothing in return" she thought. "Could all my efforts and faith be being rewarded?" she thought to herself. <br><br>She watched as the bard sped away tracking the spoor of the many Wurms that could be heard bellowing in the distance. He disappeared from view as the smoke swirled around him from the fires that raged this ravaged area. <br><br>She was left with a sense of emptiness and longing that she could not explain. Coupled with that was a hope that he would return safely so she could confirm or explain the feelings she had. <br><br>(To Be Continued)<br><br><b>To contact the author of this tale, please visit our public forum aka. <a href="http://www.lostorder.com/msgboards/conclave/">The Conclave</a>. We enjoy hearing your feedback! </b>

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
