<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Heart's Journey, Part 1</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Boladorn Stormsong  (<a href="mailto:N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
A soft drizzle spattered at his feet making the air hang heavy with the smell of decay as was normal around the docks of Freeport. Boladorn sat patiently awaiting the boat to be loaded for Faydwer and the Butcherblock Mountains. He removed his helm to allow some coolness to circulate his brow.<p>A young bard joined him at the docks and asked for some advice, they spoke about small matters, something to speed the time awaiting the boat's departure. A voice like a songbird came from behind them, startling Boladorn out of his conversation. "Pardon me sires, can either of hide me from the eyes of the corrupt guards here? I am afraid they will kill me on sight" <p>Boladorn turned and was struck by a vision of beauty the likes of which he had never seen before. "Aye lady I can keep ye unseen" he replied. He asked the beautiful Paladin to join him and removed a small pipe from his bag. He quickly looked over his notes and began playing a somber song on the pipes. The music began to move faster and Boladorn began to dance a jig, tendrils of mist began to swirl and writhe around them as if they had entered a bank of fog. Soon they disappeared from view completely. Boladorn looked up from his pipes and noticed the Paladin watching him intently. "That's quite the jig ye dance m'lord" she remarked. He winked and returned to his song.<p>The dockhands finished loading the boat and the call for passengers to board was raised. The two boarded the boat quickly and Boladorn allowed them to return to view so that they might speak to the captain. The hold was quite full and the day's rain had faded and turned into a bright and sunny one. Boladorn found a seat on stacked bails of sailcloth and admired the Paladin from his perch. <p>She turned and caught him staring. Boladorn quickly looked at the ground not wanting to show the crimson his face had turned. The Paladin approached Boladorn and took a seat next to him. "Do ye know the new continent well Bard?" she asked. "Aye, I know it well lady, I am headed that way if'n ye needs a guide" he replied.<p>Their arrival in the Butcherblock Mountains was a somber one. Crowds of people were gathered at the docks, scanning the faces of the passengers hoping to see loved ones or friends among those disembarking. Boladorn stopped one of the guards and asked what all the ruckus was about. "Pirates it seems, now move along there willna be boats from or to Kunark for the time bein." He replied and returned to policing the crowds.<p>Boladorn shrugged off the delay, but he could see the concern for those lost at sea in the Paladin's eyes. "Come with me" he said. "I'll take us to the wood elf forest and see about magical transport to the new lands" he said. As they ran he hummed a tune to make the journey flow faster.<p>They arrived without incident and began the search for an obliging wizard or druid. Several court pages from Felwithe were gathered finishing up their midday meal. Boladorn gave them each a silver and asked them to take messages to the local guild halls with requests for transportation as the boats had been waylaid by pirates.<p>The two sat and enjoyed a small snack as they waited. "Lady I fear that in our travels I have no introduced myself. I am Boladorn Stormsong of the Lost Order of Akalabeth" he said. She looked at him and smiled and replied: "I am Kahlani Lar of Knight of Cestus Vie" she said with a grin. "I must thank you for taking the time to guide me in my travels m'lord, not many would take the time as thou hast done" she said.<p>Boladorn smiled and cleared his throat. "Lady I am headed that way so there is no trouble, and with you along the journey is not so long" he said. Presently a wizard belonging to the same order as Kahlani arrived and greeted the two travelers. "Greetins and well met friends" he said. "Dalzuth my friend!" exclaimed Kahlani as she rushed over to greet the wizard. The situation was explained and Dalzuth agreed to transport the travelers to the new continent. As Dalzuth began his incantations Boladorn looked at Kahlani and saw a small hint of worry in her eye. He reached over and clasped her hand and winked at her. The worry fell from her face, and she returned his smile with a wink.<p>Boladorn knew from that moment that this journey would prove to be more interesting. <p>(To be continued) <P><b>Have a comment to make about this story? Visit: <a href="http://www.lostorder.com/msgboards/conclave" target="_top">The Conclave</a> and post your thoughts.<p>Delivered by Brimstone of Akalabeth</b>

