The twilight of Unrest always seemed magical. It was like a viscous liquid that rippled as you walked through it. So fitting was this aura though. The Estate of Unrest was surely one of magic. The dwarven spirit that haunted and perverted it had done so for ages. This day, however, it was time for him to rest. Six adventurers, sent by their beloved council, were to probe deep into the depths of Unrest and find this spirit. The Fier&#8217;dal Elders had sent them to either convince the spirit to depart or dispose of it. The reward was grand, though the peace of mind that would accompany Faydwer would be much appreciated. <br><br><center>--------------------------------</center><br>And so stood the six; A ranger, a paladin, a dastardly rogue, a druid, a cleric, and a mighty wizard. They were all of different race, all of different religion. Yet aligned in this righteous task they stood as friends, as companions, and even as brothers. Such had not been so forever, though. <br><br>Cobus Mistwielder walked through the tranquil Faydark. Such a lovely place, so bright under the gracious sun. It was the home of the ranger, the forest was always his home. It never dawned on him that the forest could be a place of danger. There was always a place to run to, a place to hide, even a place to fight. The ranger gleamed in his brilliant green chain mail, a testament to his adventures. His shady blonde hair and dark brown eyes were so rightly elven. What was a wood elf without all those sharp features, anyway? <br><br>He was on his way to Kaladim to meet up with an old friend whom he had not seen for weeks. Such a trek did involve quite a bit of time. As so, he began to invoke himself with the spirit of the wolf. His feet became faster and the forest disappeared into a blur, though he still felt as if he was walking. Tunare treated her servants well. He could be in Kaladim by the next dawn. All was quiet, until he heard the cry of battle. He decided to investigate these cries, finding what he had expected.<br><br>A young high elven couple was being menaced by a band of orcs. The male was doing what he could with this crude sword to slow the advance of the band, but they were already being flanked. &#8220;By Tunare&#8217;s will, the damned orcs ought to stop their petty attacks!&#8221; Cobus thought to himself. He drew his blades and set into battle.<br><br>Cobus unleashed a small lightning bolt at the lead orc, dropping it dead. The others turned to face him, stunned but enraged. Two orcs ran straight toward him, while others continued to attack the couple. Cobus maneuvered beautifully, placing himself between the orcs. His angled blade slashed the weapon-wielding hand of one orc, while his wakizashi sliced the tendons of the other orcs ankles. Both fell to the ground in pain, one unable to move. Cobus finished his assault in a whirlwind of blades, leaving two dead orcs.<br><br>The others, seeing their leaders killed began to back away from the couple. As Cobus started toward them, they ran off in terror. Cobus approached the shaken couple.<br>&#8220;Are you both alright?&#8221;<br>&#8220;Yes thank you!&#8221; The high elf male said, &#8220;Thank Tunare you came when you did! I am Cyrus Highmoon, noble of Felwithe. You shall be greatly rewarded for your courage&#8221; <br>Cobus turned to the female, taking her hand and giving it a light kiss, &#8220;You must be Celliya Highmoon, then. It is a pleasure to meet such a compassionate one to those less fortunate.&#8221; <br>She returned his comment &#8220;I am indeed. I am very grateful of your help. What was your name? I didn&#8217;t catch it earlier&#8221; <br>&#8220;My name is not important. Instead of paying me money, do your best to continue your great work. The community of elves is only greatened by your labour .&#8221;<br>&#8220;As it is, farewell then ranger. And thank you again for your deeds!&#8221; The couple walked off at a steady pace in the direction of Felwithe.<br>Such was the life of a ranger. So much good done, yet never any credit. That was how Tunare wanted it, no? <br>&#8220;Stay on track. Kaladim isn&#8217;t all that far&#8221; he told himself as he once again asked Tunare for the blessing of wolf speed.<br><br><br>In the holy halls of Kaladim, Berglad Stormbane sat studying some of the ancient lore that was kept there. In all his training, he had taken the time to learn to read and write. Such was uncommon amongst the dwarves. It was unfortunate, for the dwarves could tell stories well. Tales of valor, bravery, compassion filled the ancient texts. It made one proud to be of dwarven heritage, even as proud as the paladin. As he reached the end of a particularly impressive story, a knock came to his door. <br><br>&#8220;Stormbane, there is a green wood elf here to see ye. Shall&#8217; I lettimin?&#8221; Berglad knew at once he it was.<br>&#8220;Aye, let him in!&#8221;<br>In stepped his closest friend, the tree-hugging ranger who caused so much trouble in their past.<br>&#8220;Cobus! Ha ha! Where have yo&#8217;been yea tree hugging elf!&#8221;<br>&#8220;Obviously roaming around endlessly bored. Or else why would I be here?&#8221;<br>Berglad snickered &#8220;Come sit down. Would ya have me fetch some ale?&#8221;<br>&#8220;Not now, old friend. It seems I have some business to discuss.&#8221;<br>Berglad recognized the tell-tale expression of Cobus. He was really here for business.<br>&#8220;Alright, out with it.&#8221;<br>&#8220;It seems the council has had enough with Unrest. Innocent fishermen are being injured and even killed by night as they take cover from the rain. They want someone to go in and banish that ghost that haunts the basement. I think we ought to give it a shot&#8221;<br>Berglad contemplated the offer before him.<br>&#8220;So you wan&#8217;us to accomplish what no one else has done? And for what? Are ye rich en&#8217;ff already?&#8221;<br>&#8220;You know the myths as well as I do. Those boots are supposed to carry great magic. What a great prize. Not to mention that I . . we might finally be commended for doing something good.&#8221;<br>&#8220;Have you talked to the others? What do they think?&#8221;<br>&#8220;I haven&#8217;t had a chance to even contact them. I am always coming up with these schemes. With you behind me, it&#8217;ll be much easier to convince them to come along.&#8221; Cobus&#8217; face turned in a silly half grin.<br>&#8220;Would be nice to fight together again, too.&#8221;<br>Berglad couldn&#8217;t agree more. &#8220;It&#8217;as been too long.  .  . Alright alright.  Undead have always been something I enjoy destroying anyway. Plus, these boots are getting old&#8221;, Berglad clanked his plate mail boots to the floor.<br> &#8220;How long has it been since you even wore the old tunic and wielded the sword?&#8221;<br>&#8220;Too long Cobus, too long. I hope I am still in shape enough to carry them. I guess we ought to go out and find Aeril.&#8221;<br>&#8220;Already started looking for him. I heard he was still trying to fix up that tower in the Lesser Faydark. I say it&#8217;s worth a trip. You with me old man?&#8221;<br>Berglad growled. &#8220;I am not that much older than you! Stop callin&#8217; me that before I smash your small head.&#8221;<br>&#8220;Always with the violence,&#8221; chuckled Cobus.<br><br>Berglad always looked funny in his armor. His beard always got messed and just plain clashed. His mithril breastplate shined lavender in the sunlight, while his massive Ghoulbane was like a beacon. Its light could be seen from even the greatest distance. Almost like an invitation to danger, though most beings knew better. The only things that were not stereotypically dwarven about Berglad were his eyes. Bright green, they were a seeming rarity amongst dwarves. He walked alongside Cobus at a steady pace. Although Cobus wanted to enhance their speed, Berglad wanted to enjoy the scenery a bit. He didn&#8217;t get outside of Kaladim all that much. It was nice once and a while. The Butcherblocks were such a magnificent chain of mountains. It was like a natural defense of Kaladim, while at the same time providing a home. Sure, they were plagued with goblins, but what was a couple of goblin tribes against the might of Kaladim? They walked for most of the day and placed a camp near the valley into the Greater Faydark. During the night, they were awakened by a young wood elf male, with blood-ridden clothes. <br><br>Berglad woke first, starring groggily at the wood elf.<br>&#8220;Whattis it youngster?&#8221;<br>&#8220;Vampires. They&#8217;re in the Faydark. Mistmoore sent them to break up a celebration to Tunare. My family . . help please!!<br>The final shout woke Cobus fully.<br>&#8220;What is wrong child?&#8221; he asked.<br>&#8220;Cobus, get your gear. It seems Mistmoore decided to raid in on a grand party.&#8221;<br><br>The young wood elf spoke &#8220;You must hurry please! There is a mighty druid who is holding them off, but he cannot last forever.&#8221;<br>Cobus and Berglad exchanged quick glances and hurried their pace. It seems their meeting with Aeril would come more swiftly that they thought. <br>

