<P>
IN THE COMPANY OF WOE, Part One<br>by Lane Boyd (boyd@io.com)<br>Copyright April, 2000<P>The bridges of Kelethin vexed Wigglewood. They were arduous in the bright of day -- or rather, the dimness of day, as the sun never saw the floor of the misty northern Faydark woods -- but in the rain, they were slippery and swayed with the wind. Built high up in massive conifer trees, the city was series of platforms, perfect protection for the wood elves against the enemies roaming the land down below. But for a halfling born in a hole in the ground, it was trial of nerves versus will. And today it was raining.</P><P><IMG SRC="/eqshots/Image1.jpg" WIDTH=181 HEIGHT=181 align=right>Nyaleen held her hands over his head, attempting in vain to keep the halfing remotely dry. "Thanks anyway," he said, crossing the last bridge between their sleeping quarters to the nearest tavern. "But I&#8217;m already a river. Lord Karana hates me." </P><P>Entering the small wooden house with the twin, overflowing mugs painted above the door, they welcomed the warmth of the fire burning along one wall, and the shelf of bottled drinks occupying the other. Chattering customers filled a few of the tables and most of the chairs, paying no attention to the pair. "I think it's rained every day since I&#8217;ve been here," Wigglewood said. He shook himself off and let Nyaleen take his backpack. </P><P><IMG SRC="/eqshots/Image2.jpg" WIDTH=181 HEIGHT=181 align=right></P><P>At the counter, he bought a bottle of gnomish spirits from the mug-washing bartender and ordered a plate of cheese and bread. He looked around for signs of other available treats. "Is there any Mulberry pie, today?" </P><P>The bartender flipped the wet towel over his arm. "Sold the last piece not two customers ago," he said, indifferently returning his attention to the mugs, filing them in a space under the bar.</P><P>The halfling shuffled to the fireplace, glum. Mulberry was the only pie he really liked. It seemed to him that someone, an enemy for certain, was always one step ahead, buying up the best of the local delicacies, the lack of which was acerbated by the general wood elf reluctance to open a decent shop at ground level.</P><P>Nyaleen, however, was more glum than he. She was young and fire-hearted, but the onus of habitual battle wasn't an enemy she could slay and be done with. Her olive skin, once youthful, was etched with the weight of accountability. She was not soft; she was fierce. Nature didn't commune with her as it did with her brethren. She was the product of an increasingly militant race, obligated not to the forests and the animals that inhabit them, but to the weapons she could find to defend herself. Wigglewood passed her the cheese and poured her a glass of the drink. He exaggerated a sigh and was about to begin a denunciation of the bartender, when Nyaleen spoke first.</P><P>"I haven't heard from my contact in Neriak for months," she said. "I want you to go to the Common Lands, find him, see what trouble he's making or whatever it is he's gotten into."</P><P>Wigglewood swallowed the entirety of his glass and searched absently for his pipe in his many pockets. Or perhaps something to smoke once he found it. "You hired a Tier'Dal," he said, distracted. "Dark elves likes trouble. What do you care?"</P><P>"I hired him to keep me informed, but with his chronic lapses, I know less now that I did when I worked alone."</P><P>The halfling stopped the searching, fruitless. The pipe was as gone today as it was yesterday and the day before that. He needed to remember to buy a new one, or at least remember that the old one was missing. "I'm not so sure I want to go to the Common Lands,&quot; he said. &quot;I haven't done anything here except be your personal merchant. I want to look around, have a go at these orcs you fight so much. You know battles I've fought? Spiders and bats and other belly-to-the-ground things. Boring. You can't pay me enough to keep me from my own training any longer."</P><P>"I don't pay you at all."</P><P>"Harumph. Certainly you don't. I'm a merchant. I earn my own way." He folded and unfolded his arms, then sat on the stool next to the fire without returning her stare. She sat as she always did, cross-legged on the wooden floor a few feet away, ignoring his wry tone. Wigglewood scratched his forehead. "Sorry, Ny, but being an amateur trader in city full of professionals is more than frustrating. It's ridiculous."</P><P>"I know it is," she said. "You're a priest of Lord Bristlebane and you should be memorizing your devotions. So why not catch the next ship to Freeport? You can make a pilgrimage to Rivervale. I'll handle the sells."</P><P>He snorted and lifted a hunk of cheese from the plate on the eave of the fireplace. "So you say, concerned warrior," he said, biting and chewing and talking at the same time. He paused to swallow and brush crumbs from his fingers. "Here's what I think you mean to say: To hell with Neriak, go find your sister Rendi, make sure she's safe in her woodland retreat, but don't tell her you've asked after her. Don't tell her you're worried that we haven't heard from her since she left. Don't tell her you mope around the woods instead of finishing your training. Your peers have all earned their surname, but not you, not yet. Rendi doesn't need to know that, right?"</P><P>Nyaleen stood at the unexpected scolding, anger abruptly contorting her face. The halfling twitched, not the least reassured that her weapons were sheathed and stored in her bags. He shied away from her when she moved toward him, but it was only the beginning of a fretful pace, trapped between Wigglewood, the fireplace, and the wall of the tavern.</P><P>The halfling leaned forward, bracing his elbows on his knees and chin on the palm of his wide hands. She was troubled, and not by an absent sibling. "Why don't you go to Freeport instead of me?" he offered</P><P>She wrung her hands together uncharacteristically. The firelight shone red over her forehead, drawing sharp shadows over her black hair and into the corners of her eyes. "I can't leave Faydwar right now, friend. As you said, I haven't completed my training, but you're wrong that I'm not working on it. I have been, just slowly."</P><P>"There's no reason you can't finish your training elsewhere. Warriors are needed in every land."</P><P>She shook her head. "I'm an Emerald Warrior. What I started here, I will finish." She gnawed at her bottom lip. "That, and I've been having bad dreams. Not the kind when I'm sleeping, but when I'm fighting, a hit takes me down and I'm out. I wake up in a nightmare, where I'm here, back home, a naked soul, alone and far from my body. I'm compelled to race against a demon, a malicious demon, to find my body before he swipes it away to the hells. I run and I run until I find it." She brushed her hair back from where it fell wetly in her face. "Each time I regain my body, there's a small part of me that's been lost forever, as if it's been wiped away and I have to live that part of my life over again. And each time I fall in battle, the nightmare is worse, the lost part of me even greater."</P><P>Wigglewood nodded. He pointed to her cobolt blue armor. "Is that why you accepted the expensive centaur armor from one of your warrior friends? I was told that it's awarded only to those who have earned it."</P><P>"I'm alive," she snorted. She returned to her seat on the floor with a metallic thud. "I consider it earned."</P><P>The halfling flushed. She was reaching out and he answered with a slap to an open wound. He obviously wasn't the first to question the armor, prized even in the merchant circles. That would have to be an issue resolved on another day. He clapped his hands together. "No sense in sticking around Kelethin if there's no mulberries," he said. He shouldered his worn leather backpack and took a deep breath to get her attention off the floor. When she looked up, he gave her a grin. "And I'll have to get some supplies if I'm going on a trip."</P><P ALIGN="CENTER">***</P><P>Rain continued to fall. The small drops forced a path through the forest's canopy, splattering against the leaves, making it worse for the travelers, the spray of water flicking unexpectedly in their eyes, blurring their vision. Wigglewood held the rope handles tightly and never looked down. He was raised in a hole. Only birds should live so high.</P><P>The platform headquarters of the Emerald Warriors was hidden among the branches of the giant trees. The canopy here was thick and broad, shielding those underneath from the storm god's blessing. In the torchlight, he could see tankards of ale being passed along the rows of gnarled men and lovely women. Weather like this was kind to neither beauty nor beast.</P><P><IMG SRC="/eqshots/Image3.jpg" WIDTH=193 HEIGHT=193 align=right></P><P>Opening the door and shoving themselves in from out of the rain, they found the headquarters filled with soldiers. Most were busy in the back room, where a merchant patiently traded coins for the goods that filled the shelves. The front room contained a single desk, the official residence of the soldiers' high commander. His name was Regren, and if he wasn&#8217;t the most official wood elf Wigglewood had ever seen, he was at least the most silver. His platemail alone was impossible not to respect.</P><P>Nyaleen hailed the commander. He stood as she approached. "Sire, this is my associate, Wigglewood, a cleric of Bristlebane Fizzlethorp."</P><P>The halfling smiled wanly at the man, vaguely uncomfortable at being regarded as a holy man. He bowed slightly. "Really, I'm just here on vacation," he said.</P><P>"This is hardly a place for vacation," the commander replied, returning the bow. "But it's just as well that you&#8217;re here. Warriors rely on the mercy that priests have gained from the gods." He squinted at the halfling. "Of course, Bristlebane is the lord of thieves, is he not?"</P><P>"Bristlebane is the Overseer of the Oppressed, commander. Thieving is a necessity of life, as is a sense of humor." Wigglewood gave him his Happy Look.</P><P>Regren frowned. He addressed his subordinate. "Nyaleen, has your associate witnessed the brutality of the Crushbone clan?"</P><P>"No, sire."</P><P>Regren glowered and turned to the halfling. "You must understand the threat they hold to us, if you&#8217;re going to be a civilian of Norrath. Each person is responsible for survival of the next. Gone are the days of living alone, independent of one another. Even Nyaleen has learned that no one person can survive." He looked at her expectantly and she nodded a reply, her face rigid.</P><P>"Then when you're finished with your business here," the commander continued, "my charge will guide you into Crushbone where you will learn what our enemies are about." He smiled balefully at Nyaleen before resettling his eyes on the Wigglewood. "I know you're not trained as an Emerald Warrior, my friend, but I still take it upon myself to educate you about the local dangers. Use your skills wisely."</P><P>The halfling rocked back and forth on his prodigious toes. "I was about to go on a long trip, but you're right. I should have more experience." He winked over his shoulder at Nyaleen. She wore the fierce face again.</P><P>"Yes sir," she said, saluting her commander, her face tactfully shifting from fierce to dutiful. "I&#8217;ll give him the Crushbone tour immediately." Though she might be Wigglewood's friend and, by common history, a cousin, she was above all a soldier. "I worried for his safety, commander, that's why I haven't shown him the castle earlier."</P><P>Regren was already studying a new scroll. He grunted and nodded, obviously trying to return to the other matters. "Good luck with your training, Nyaleen," he said, dismissing them.</P><P ALIGN="CENTER">***</P><P>Faces of soldiers drifted in and out of the mist on the path leading north out Kelethin. Dour men and women returning home silently passed Wigglewood by; others sat in make-shift camps on hillsides and under trees, watching nothing or eating or wiping their weapons clean. The halfling couldn't take time to stare, pressed as he was to keep up with Nyaleen's quick pace further into the Faydark woods. He wasn't doing so well, hampered by chainmail armor that laid over him like a net. She'd given it to him when he arrived in the elven city, but he never wore it. It was heavy. The tunic was bad enough, the leggings pieces and the coif were plain cruel. He slogged over the mossy ground, trying to keep sight of the warrior one hilltop ahead. She moved surpisingly fast in all that metal. </P><P>A howl of pursuit severed Wigglewood's progress as Nyaleen once again disappeared over a crest. A tattered soldier broke from the trees onto the path in front of him. The halfling veered to give the man room to run, but a second figure, then a third and a fourth pierced the veil of mist, each futilely striking out at their elusive quarry. Scrambling to gain ground, they pushed Wigglewood aside. All the halfing saw was black blue fur, vicious teeth, and monstrous arms, hunched as they trampled him, intent on the soldier ahead. Their wake was filled with the smell of a seasoned bathhouse. </P><P>Wigglewood gagged, falling to his knees. Explosions of white and red light erupted over the horizon behind him, drowned out by the clang of blades and an exchange of curses. Then the sound of running carried the conflict away. </P><P>The halfling stared down the path, listening. His breath caught, overwhelmed by fear that the beasts would quickly return, this time to end the halfling's meddling in their lands. He forced himself quietly to his feet, checking the ground for dropped items.</P><P>A glint of color startled him. He bolted a step to the left and lifted the mace he'd forgotten about in his hand, striking out haphazardly at the movement.</P><P>"Watch that," Nyaleen said, dodging the blow. She stood, unwinded, in the middle of the path, examining the surrounding land intently. She held twin blades at the ready, sharp glimmering extensions of her arms. "Did I lose you?"</P><P>"No, there was a chase involving one soldier and three beasts close behind." Wigglewood held his breath at the memory. "Oy, they smelled. And all four of them mistook me for the path. The soldier nearly ran me over." Wigglewood rubbed his head and looked for a place to put his mace, but didn't find one. "I guess I wouldn't have given me much thought, either, with enemies like those on my heels." Nyaleen was watching him silently. "So those are orcs, all smell and no manners?"</P><P>"Small ones, yep." She turned back in the direction of the rising hills and Crushbone Castle on the other side. "Are you ready? The mist is opening up a bit, we should be able to stay clear of anyone else on the hunt."</P><P>"Hunting? So far everything out here feels like a footrace." He shouldered his pack and started north on the trail behind the warrior, who jogged slightly faster than a quick walk.</P><P>"Yank and spank," she said without turning. "Cull one from the group and ambush it in safer territory. The fellow that ran you over yanked too hard, had to make the run back to the city guards. That's the thing about orcs, once they're in a fight, they love a good chase. They'd run right into a bed full of hornets if you went in first. That's why the yank and spank works so well. And why it goes wrong so quickly. A smart warrior knows where his friends are. Remember that. I've probably lead just as many to their doom as I've killed myself. Still do, when necessary."</P><P>Wigglewood adjusted his backpack, pulling his feet from the moss to keep up with her. "Uh, yeah," he said. "You know, maybe I'm changing my mind about this whole adventure. I'll could explain to Regren that I suffer from back pains, and then make him a deal on some leather whips I haven't been able to move."</P><P>"I don't want him mad at me. Do you want him mad at me, when I'm this close to completing my training?" She displayed two gauntletted fingers held a smidgen apart. "And I thought I said to give those whips away if they didn't sell."</P><P>Wigglewood sighed, exasperated and wet with collecting humidity. The constant woodland mist rolled dramatically over them, a beast of a different flavor. "I'm supposed to give stuff away, Ny? You said I was here to make a profit, not a social conscious. That's your job." </P><P>Forced to watch his feet instead of the path ahead, the halfling bumped into the back of her legs with the top of his head. She stood immobile in the path. "What?" he said. "Are you angry at me again?" </P><P>The warrior pointed into the mist with one of her blades. "See how the path goes up, and ends in where those fires are burning?"</P><P>Wigglewood peered around her armor. He couldn't see more than ten paces ahead. "Yeah, kinda," he lied.</P><P>"That's the entrance to Crushbone, heavily guarded by a gang of orc centurions."</P><P>Wigglewood dropped his mace with a thud. "A gang?" </P><P>"Aye," she nodded, and indicated with her sword for him to crouch as she did. "Listen."</P><P>Under the breath of the forest, he heard the crackling of fire. "Fire, right, I hear that," he whispered hoarsely. When she didn't reply, her tall ears practically bending forward to catch the nuances of tree sounds, the halfling scanned what he could see, anxious. To the left and slightly forward, a simple stone monument rose up indefinitely into the fog like an unmarked headstone in a giant cemetery. He turned his head away, disturbed by the image, only to further surprise. An empty tent stared back at him with its open flap. It was nuzzled up next to another monument identical to the one on his left. The bleeding corpse of an elven soldier lay next to a black heap of decaying orc flesh.</P><P>Wigglewood tapped on Nyaleen's armor. "Ny, I --"</P><P>"Shhhh," she interrupted. "Here they come."</P><P>His skin prickled in alarm. They, a gang of orcs? He swiped up his fallen mace and raised it like a shield, even though the warrior remained in a crouch. "What are you waiting for?" he demanded. Then abruptly, a whooping war cry broke from behind him, and rush of soldiers -- elven and other -- flew past the pair and charged up the path until they were only shadows. They were answered by beasts.</P><P>"Let's go, stay close." Nyaleen jogged forward as quick as possible without losing Wigglewood, which meant half running, half lumbering sideways so she could keep an eye on him. The path ended in an open stretch that fed into the maw of a wide tunnel in a rising mountainside. The soldiers who'd dashed past them had drawn the four orc sentries away from the entrance and engaged them near a massive bonfire to the left, surrounding them with a flurry of blades and maces.</P><P>Wigglewood almost overran Nyaleen as they dodged around the battle and sprinted into the tunnel. He wasn't convinced that other centurions weren't hiding in anticipation of such a maneuver. Once inside, Nyaleen hugged the stone wall, as she led him around a sharp corner. The tunnel continued straight for only a short distance before turning again toward Crushbone. A ring of soldiers sat against the walls in the pocket of space in-between turns, as if holding the tunnel interior as a refuge against the orc camps. </P><P>Now, holes in the ground were among Wigglewood's favorite things. A snug burrow, a mug of warm plum wine and a riddle upon which to chew. A warren he'd call home. Toss in a mulberry pie, and he'd never leave. But as the daydream wrapped cozily around him, the mountain pass made him shiver, wiping away the rumination with a brush of stagnant air. </P><P>"Ugh. Smells worse than orcs in here."</P><P>"That would be the dead ones. We leave their bodies as a warning. The pass is ours," she said. Wigglewood looked around uneasily, more than a little revolted over the conduct of war. "At first I felt sorry for them," she said, watching his reaction, "but I came to understand that Emperor Crush desires nothing more than our utter destruction, and it's only by careful and methodical weeding of their ranks do we keep them from returning to power. Leave them alone for a day, or even a night, and they swell to impossible numbers." </P><P>"That's not reassuring," he said, even more anxious. He looked over the room's contingent. Half were bandaged and staring into nothing while others raptly studied tattered books and half-torn scrolls. Another few stood guard over the rest, swords drawn against imminent attacks.</P><P>Nyaleen put her hand on his shoulder. "We're here all the time, my friend. There's little to worry about. Ready to go on?" </P><P>"No," he said, watching her proceed further into the tunnel. He hefted his backpack and followed. He trudged through the dimness until, around the next turn, he could see the clear sky of Crushbone shining at the end of the pass. Morning had broken. Nyaleen stood in the open area beyond the pass, inspecting the grounds he couldn't quite yet see. When the warrior waved for him to join her, he hefted his mace confidently and started forward at once. Not only was there no clinging mist to weigh on him, but he could see clearly for the first time since arriving in Kelethin. His heart lifted. He even remembered the mulberry pie he was planning to eat for lunch. He could almost taste it.</P><P>Wigglewood stopped before he reached the end of the pass. An alcove that was at one time shaped by a frame of round stones was now filled in with a gray mortar. The result was rough and flaky to the touch, but in the shadow of the pass, the mortar was barely discernable from the rest of the wall. </P><P>Nyaleen hollered at him, "What are you doing?"</P><P>"On my way," he shouted back, but when he turned to wave at her, the mortar burst out from the wall, dropping at his feet. A furry blue hand shot out from the concealed space and grabbed him around the throat.</P><P>&quot;Halflings like you are better left dead than alive,&quot; an orc cursed from inside the hidden recess. It pulled him into the remaining mortar, cutting his forehead on the sharp, dry edge, then ramming his left temple into an actual stone in the wall. The orc let Wigglewood fall to the ground so it could smash away the rest of the mortar. The halfling crawled backward during the few seconds he had, feeling for the mace he had dropped once again.</P><P>&quot;Death to all those who oppose the Crushbone orcs!&quot; the orc cried out, swinging a rusty blade down at him. Wigglewood rolled out of its way and smashed at the hairy knees with the mace. Surprisingly, he hit, but it only enraged the beast. Howling, the orc slashed the mace, almost knocking it from the halfling's hands, then struck again, this time crushing his shoulder with the blunt blade. The ringmail armor prevented it from reaching skin, but that didn't lessen the pain. Wigglewood's upper right arm bristled numb.</P><P>"Help!" he yelled, finding his feet and backing away as the orc pressed its assault. "Nyaleen, help!" Under the onslaught, he couldn't get the mace balanced to attack. He held it like a metal staff, fending off his opponent's continuous blows. The beast knew it had the physical advantage, and Wigglewood imagined that it was daydreaming of halfling stew. Though its only armor was a rag of a shirt and shiny silver belt buckle, the orc was taller, stronger, and had teeth like a mean dog that it liked to gnash and lick with a nasty black tongue. He knew the battle would be lost if the beast breathed directly on his face.</P><P>"Sorry, Wig," Nyaleen said from nearby. She was behind him in the tunnel, evaluating the fight. "The more I think about it, then more I know Regren is right. You've got to learn to fend for yourself. When you go to the Common Lands, I won't be there."</P><P>"What, are you crazy?" He dodged a strike to his head and managed to swing his mace at the orc in return. The orc sidestepped the blow and redoubled its efforts, slashing the halfling's cheek and then crushing his wrist when he tried to protect his face. "I'm going to die here!"</P><P>Nyaleen's answer was soft but adamant. "This might sound cruel, cousin, but you're going to have to kill him yourself. This is the way we learn."</P><P>Bewildered, Wigglewood fled the tunnel for open ground. The orc followed, clubbing him ruthlessly across the back. Only the sight of other soldiers nearby kept him from falling to his knees, for surely one of them would come to his rescue. Get lifted the mace and swung wildly behind him, forcing the orc to take a step back. He saw Nyaleen closely following the beast, but still not coming to his aid.</P><P>"Fight him with your strength," she said, "not with your weakness."</P><P>It was if her advice formed into a hook that breached his heart and drew the heat of wrath across the surface of his skin. He pummeled the orc back with a blow to its neck, pushing it back a step, "Why don't you just tell me what the hells you mean," he said, spitting the words out. &quot;I can't figure it out right now!" </P><P>"Wig, do you know how to use that mace?"</P><P>"No, gods, no! Help me!" </P><P>The orc's next slash didn't reach him. As the centurion lifted the rusty blade to strike down on Wigglewood's head, Nyaleen swatted its sword arm with one blade and cut across its unprotected back with the other. The orc turned to protect itself, leaving the halfling free to gasp for air and unceremoniously collapse to one knee. "Prayer," Nyaleen said. "Pray for the power of your Lord Bristlebane. Don't you remember your own training?" She seemed undisturbed by the orc's swordplay, easily parrying blows while holding a conversation. </P><P>"I can't pray for help with a beast at my throat," he choked. </P><P>"Exactly." She batted the orc's head between her blades, striking quickly with one then the other, but only surface wounds. She wasn't going for the kill. This drove the orc insane, a clever ploy to distract the beast from the fact that it now faced a much greater foe. </P><P>A greater foe, indeed, Wigglewood told himself. Nyaleen attacked with swift calculation, completely unrestricted by her armor's weight or binding fit. Her armor moved with her, not against, enhancing her already formidable skills. The halfling kicked himself for chiding her about accepting the armor. It was like a partner, complementing instead of simply defending. Watching her, his anger turned away from her and into himself. She's been training constantly to hone her skills, while he'd merely run from his.</P><P>She does deserve her surname, he thought. She's a killer fighting for her homeland, and what am I but a prayerful man? A painful man, that's what I am.</P><P>He struggled to his feet, his head throbbing and favoring his left side. A rib felt broken. Worse, a rage built up inside him. The orc's beating reshaped the mercy of Bristlebane into scorn. Nyaleen held the beast between her blades, watching her associates' response.</P><P>"Make the summons," she told him over the orc's howls and shrieks. "Bristlebane is everything for you."</P><P>Imagining himself in a dark room, a single candle lighting his face, he called on his master. <I>O Bristlebane, this orc is not built to last.</I> Immediately, clarity returned to his senses, pushing out the misery and replacing it with relief. His arms took on a life of their own, completing a complicated swirl of forearm and fingers. His fingertips tingled, and a red flash of light crashed around the orc. It crumpled to the ground, accompanied by a rumble of thunder.</P><P>Wigglewood sat heavily. As if on signal, rain started to fall. He looked up into it, letting the cool drops drain away the heat away from his face.</P><P>"Karana blesses you," Nyaleen said. She stood over the centurion&#8217;s body and used her blades to cut away the beast's belt. With a flick of her wrist, she tossed the leather and silver prize into his hands.</P><P>"Loot," he said, feeling at the silver with a thumb. "Bristlebane blesses me, too."</P><P>The warrior guffawed. "There is a man in Kaladim who will reward you well for that buckle."</P><P>Wigglewood touched his side and his forehead. He knew he should feel worse than he did, but there was more to Bristlebane's mercy than a shock to the orc. He felt refreshed. His head no longer throbbed, and the sting had been cleansed from the cut on his cheek. "I don't know," he said. "I might keep this one for myself."</P><P>Nyaleen smiled serenely at him, youthfulness replacing the toughed warrior for an instant. "Ready to get out of here?"</P><P>"I am, yes. Please." He took her proffered hand and let himself be pulled to his feet.</P><P>She slapped him on the shoulder and helped him adjust his backpack. "Nice smite, by the way." </P><P>"I wouldn't call it a smite," he said. "More like a holy pie in the face."</P><P>She laughed, "Mulberry pie, maybe?"</P><P>Wigglewood licked his lips. "Definitely mulberry!" He swung the centurion&#8217;s belt in a circle around his free hand. "Say, Kaladim's on the way to the docks to Freeport, isn't it?"</P><P>She laughed again, walking next to him through the pass, tapping one blade on the stones in the wall, careful against a second ambush. Soldiers ran obliviously around them on their way in and out of Crushbone. One emergency over, another about to begin. </P><B><I><P>End of part 1</P>

