<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">First Adventure to Kunark</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Ezno Eyebiter  (<a href="mailto:N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
I, Ezno Eyebiter, High Scholar of the Heroes of the Avatar scribe this account of our initial expeditions to the continent of Kunark so that future Heroes may study this strange new land to help in their exploration of it. <br><br>Impatiently we awaited the building of the outpost.  During this time of construction, we sent our chief scout, Molan Toejam, to do some initial exploration of this land and bring us word of his discoveries.  Many dangerous creatures he faced in bringing us this information, and bravely he fought on this new land as he explored its secrets.  When our faithful druid finally made his way back to us it was with great gain, and with great loss.  <br><br>In a great battle with a mountain giant encountered in the Dreadlands, our scout was suffered a great injury that has left his right leg severely mangled.  We thank the gods in allowing his final spell, a spell of succor, to succeed in bringing him home alive.   Thus far, our clerics have been able to do nothing for the injury and we all fear his days of exploration have ended.  However, many of us do not give up hope that new healing spells may be uncovered that can heal his injury and restore his full health to us.<br><br>I spent weeks with Molan, one of my dearest halfling friends, speaking of his explorations in the new lands.  In these talks I gathered that two important discoveries had been made: <br><br>The first, and most exciting to one of the mystical arts, are the ruins of the Combine Empire.   Though not certain, through descriptions that were given to me, I believe we may have found the ancient seat of power of the largest and greatest civilization that graced the face of Norrath.   <br><br>The second, and most suprising, discovery was of a new race of lizard-like men known as the Iskar.  These creatures seem highly intelligent and yet barbaric at the same time.  Their viciousness and cruelty seems to know no bounds, and yet they seem to be a highly organized and close knit society where traits such as dishonesty and dishonor have no place.   Molan was able to view their city from a distance and even catch glimpse of several in his travels.  Most information, however, has come from the initial elven explorers who first made contact with the Iskar and who first felt their wrath.   <br><br>If all reports are correct, these two discoveries are connected.  Most of the ruins found scattered about the continent point towards one startling conclusion.  The combine empire was once ruled by these very same Iskar.  It is a startling discovery which only leads to more questions.  If these are the descendents of the great rulers of that empire, what happened to bring them to their current state?   These questions would have to wait until we could do more exploration.<br><br>Finally, the day had arrived and our first real excursion unit had departed for the new lands.  After much heated discussion, we decided to send a very small band of adventurers in our initial unit to gather more information.  The barbarians Kardadar and Sarita, a warrior and shaman, were chosen for this.  I was delighted to also be included in this group.   <br><br>We sailed upon a huge elven war galley to the outpost and were greeted by the elven guards at the docks.  We made our way around the outpost, which is still under construction, and found ourselves lodging for the night.  Early in the morning  I was greeted by a very eager Kard who insisted we immediately set out for parts unknown and find glorious battle.  <br><br>Having heard that agents of Mistmoore were spotted in the forests outside of the outpost, we set off through the tunnels to investigate.  We joined up with Cron and Gildon of the Highland Army on the beach and quickly spotted the evil spider-like beings that Mayong had sent.  <br><br>The beasts are an abomination, obviously constructs of a dark and evil magic which has combined the torso of a dark elf with the body of a spider.  The foul beasts were quick to attack and fought with fang and magic.   After a chaotic melee we finally beat back their forces and were able to treat our wounded.  We had slain many of the abominations, but still spotted many more moving under the trees.   <br><br>We decided to send Kardadar on a quick scouting run to survey the area.   A few hours later we were greeted by a great yell and the sight of an injured Kard running from another large force of the spiders.  A  quick prayer of healing from Gildon saved our barbarian friend from certain death.  The rest of us jumped to our feet and engaged the spiders, Cron singing a soothing song to mesmerise a few as Sarita, a newly healed Kard and myself sprang into battle with the rest.   Again, we were successful in beating them back.  <br><br>We set up a guarded camp for the night and Kard informed us of another great evil lying further into the woodlands.  A tribe of evil frogloks had taken up residence in some ruins a few leagues from the outpost.  The next morning, Kard led us to this place.  The trip was beautiful, passing under the great oaks and traveling alongside a trickling stream, but otherwise uneventful as we were masked in a cloak of invisibility for our travels.  Finally, near mid day, we made it to the ruins and engaged the frogloks.  We battled their knights with our sword and their shamans with our magic and, after a grueling melee, had slain over two dozen of the enemy and forced the rest to retreat.   <br><br>It was nearing evening, thus we moved ourselves a safe distance from the ruins and setup another guarded camp.   The next morning, after a heated discussion where Kard demanded to go slay more of the frogloks, Sarita and I were able to calm him enough to follow Cron&#8217;s suggestion of reporting back to the outpost our findings.  Through the use of his bardic powers, we were able to quickly travel back to the outpost and give our reports to an elven captain.  <br><br>I must admit, after the two day excursion, I spent my night drinking much wine and felt myself feeling unwell the following morning.  With great sadness, I was forced to inform my friends that I must rest for the day to meet my cousins as they arrived on the docks.<br><br>Later that evening I was reunited with my cousins, Nizzudin Nosebiter and Ellaar Earbiter, all of the House of Bite.  We sat around the tavern that night as I told them stories of what I had witnessed and we pored over more of the notes Molan had brought back with him.  We decided that, upon the morrow, we would journey into the Dreadlands.  <br><br>We set out through the tunnel early that morning.  We emerged onto the beach to find a barbarian staring down several of the spider creatures I had fought in the days previous.  Jumping to the shaman&#8217;s aid, we threw a volley of spells at the fiends and, aided by the barbarian&#8217;s shaman magic, we were able to quickly dispatch them.   Thus, we met Stinkymaw and, after a brief discussion, he agreed to travel to the Dreadlands with us.  Aided by our spells of invisibility and his granting of the spirit of the wolf, we were able to quickly make our way to this new land.  <br><br>We emerged from the tunnel into the Dreadlands and were immediately jumped by a blue devil born not out of myth or legend, but out of our nightmares.   My air elemental was able to hold the fiend at bay as I struck it with summoned swords, Nizzudin with the heat of flames, Stinky with the cold of Everfrost and Ellaar attacked its mind.   After a great magical battle the beast was slain and we were able to take our first good look at the Dreadlands.<br><br>How can I describe this strange new land?  The trees waver in the distance high atop grassy hills.  The beasts, both fantastic and vicious, roam the land making travel perilous.  As we scouted out the area we met up with two other brave adventurers, Trees Smokem and Vump of the famous House of Ump.   Joining up with these two druids, we made our way towards some ruins we spotted in the distance.   <br><br>As we came upon the ruins, we spotted skeletal lizardmen inside.  This confirmed what our research had suspected, the foul Iskar practiced the heretical art of Necromancy.   Using our newfound friends ability to use nature against them, we lured the skeletal figures outside one by one and struck them down with our magic.   <br><br>As nightfall approached, we decided to set up camp not far from the ruins.  We set up a rotation for guarding the camp and I lay down to sleep as Trees took the first watch.  Just as I had drifted off to sleep I was jolted awake by the cries of battle.  A Mountain Giant had wandered into our camp and attacked Trees.   Vump, being quick on her feet as halflings often are, quickly ensnared the giant allowing us time to gather our forces.  Stinkymaw quickly healed Trees as my cousins and I let loose a volley of magic at the giant.   The battle with this gigantic mountain roamer was fierce and long, but after much mana had been spent the foul giant was finally struck dead.   <br><br>It was difficult to get back to sleep after such an intense melee, and luckily so.  No sooner had we gathered by our campfire than a fierce Yeti was spotted in the distance.   After a brief discussion, we decided to head out and slay this mighty beast.   As we hiked towards the clearing the snow beast stood in we were jumped, yet again, this time by a mythical cockatrice.   <br><br>After a fierce series of magical battles, we were able to destroy the cockatrice, the yeti, and another foul beast that resembled a black widow spider yet stood five feet in height.  The morning sun shown down on our tired band as we surveyed still more foul beasts roaming the land.  We decided to make a quick retreat closer to the tunnel to set up camp.  <br><br>A full day we camped there recovering our strength until we were well rested and, again, full of the adventurous spirit.   As we broke down our tents and prepared to move on, a weary ranger wandered into our camp.  Coraan of Finality had been missing and presumed dead after heading out to scout the new lands many weeks ago.  We were overjoyed to see him in our camp and bade him rest as we discussed his findings.  Many new lands he had been to and many new beasts had he slain on his travels.   Finally, weary from he constant battle, he had made his way back towards the outpost.  <br><br>As excited as I was to explore more of these new lands, I knew my duty as the high scholar of the Avatar.  I parted with my cousins and new friends and traveled with Coraan back to the elven outpost.  There, over a hot meal in the tavern, I began to take notes of his many adventures in the new lands.  <br><br>Thus comes the end of my tale, for now, Heroes.  It is now late in the night and I am still tired from my journeys.  I will send this letter in the next ship leaving for Butcherblock.   Please store it in our library until my return.   <br><br>Ezno Eyebiter<br>High Scholar of the Heroes of the Avatar,<br>Erudite Magician of the 39th circle.  

