<a name="newsitem956694055,89604,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The Pros and Cons of Kunark</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Byron Everglade  (<a href="mailto:ajbrennan@sympatico.ca" class="credit2">ajbrennan@sympatico.ca</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
	In this essay I will discuss what I believe are the major pros and cons of the new Everquest Expansion, The Ruins of Kunark. This is all my own opinion, based on first-hand experience in exploring the new zones.<br><br>	On the 'PRO' side;<br><br>+ There are many new zones, 24 I think is the official number, so this helps greatly with the overcrowding I should think.<br><br>+ There is a new character race, the Iksar which gives the player a bit more variety to choose from when creating his character.<br><br>+ Perhaps hundreds of new monster types (only Verant knows the real number at this time but there are a lot).<br><br>+ Getting there. The trip to Kunark from the docks in Butcherblock Mountains is quite an experience, the large ship that the high elves have prepared is awe inspiring. ( It could be argued that the wood elves built it when you see the architecture and style) Also , this king of the sea is FAST! Someone must have 'disarmed' it back in the coding phase =P. The trip from Oasis is ..how can I say it..less outstanding. The main ship from the Timorous ogre island does have an evil theme though so it's worth it to see.<br><br>+ The new clouds look REALLY nice. I know this probably doesn't mean much, but seriously, turn on double sky layer for a minute and take a look, they did a nice job.<br><br>	On the 'CON' side;<br><br>- Problems before the expansion even came out. Yes I know everyone knows about this problem and is probably tired of hearing it, but it IS a problem. I don't know who's fault it was but there were/are some major delays in getting the CD's out to those who ordered them. By the time you read this there are probably some people who still have not recieved it yet.<br><br>- Zones. Some of them are too large for their own good. I know you're thinking, "What is this guy talking about? Too large? What a jerk, always trying to find something to complain about". Well I'll tell you this now, some zones ARE too big for their own good. Many travelers end up following the zone wall to get somewhere, as it is the easiest way not to get lost. This is sad because I'm sure the artists did a nice job on the stuff in the middle of the zones, but it will be a while before most people get the courage to go see it. The Dreadlands for example is approximately 3 or 4 times the size of West Karana, maybe more. Some zones, like The Lake of Ill Omen incorporate 2 or more ENTIRE dungeons within their boundaries ( not as separate branching zones) thereby reducing framerate considerably for players with even top of the line systems. For example, I myself am running a Pentium II 400mhz, 128megs RAM and a TnT2 Video Card. When I was inside the narrow twisting corridors of the ****** dungeon (dont want to spoil too much)  in the Lake of Ill Omen I was getting about 15 fps at 800x600 resolution, med particle density, medium clip plane, level of detail on, 3D sky double layer. Only when I went down to 640x480 resolution and turned off all those goodies did I get a semi smooth framerate. This is terrible considering that I can go through Butcherblock or West Karana with all those goodies on and get 30+ fps. I understand that they did increase the system requirements with the expansion but this is ridiculous. With a system that is somewhere near top of the line, to be forced to play in lowest resolution is an insult to my video card.<br><br>- The partial reason for these horrid framerates is the trees. Yes, the trees. I know its nice and realistic that the trees sway in the wind, but as soon as you get more than 6 or 8 trees on screen at once, be prepared for slowdown. This is even worse in the Warsliks Woods and the Burning Woods where there are trees EVERYWHERE as far as the eye can see. The leaf covered branches are low to the ground so you can't see 10 feet in front of you. While this is good because it creates a real sense of danger, it is too much when you have 15 trees all intersecting each other and all swaying, all around you. If they include a switch to turn off the swaying trees then I think this would help greatly. In fact let my put it in bold for those of you who are just skimping through. INCLUDE A SWITCH TO TURN OFF THE SWAYING OF THE TREES. Needles to say, navigating the woods is not desirable at 15 fps as there are countless moving objects obstructing your view.<br><br>- Several sound bugs. Many creatures emit male human sounds (even female creatures) when attacked. Although Verant has addressed this, it makes no sense why this was not taken care of before the release.<br><br>- Bad pathing in places like Karnor Castle (zone in the middle of Dreadlands). Creatures will run back and forth along an invisible line several times, not 5 feet away from where you stand before finally reaching you and attacking.<br><br>- Zone Lines not defined. There are several places where a player can walk around a lone line and fall though the world. (Tread carefully in The Burning Woods). I know this first-hand as I recently took a 10,000-damage plunge to my death. (Thanks to guide Dranyl The Night Watchman, Xegony for helping me). <br><br>	Now, I should say that not ALL zones are as bad as this at all times, some times if you are not looking around too much then you will be fine, but the majority of the zones that I have seen suffer from these problems. That being said, I'm not saying the new expansion is worthless, but it is not perfect, far from it I'm sad to say. Maybe Ill go back and look around again and try to get back into it. I did pay for this thing...<br><br>Byron Everglade, Xegony

<!-- End Content -->
