<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Toadentrop's Trial</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Robert Hansen  (<a href="mailto:ghost@madbbs.com" class="credit2">ghost@madbbs.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
"So yer off to see the war are ye?" inquired the man behind the counter.<br>Toadentrop politely smiled and payed the man in gold for the passage slip and made his way back out of the  building. He knew what would be waiting for him. A reception that he was not exactly prepared for.  His comrades of this past year would be just outside ready to make one last bid to talk him out of going.  But this, this was his home in danger, and their homes.  Quickly his eyes adjusted to the bright haze that hangs in the square out side the Freeport customs house, and there they were. <br><br>Though there is a wide variety of peoples in Freeport it certainly was easy to spot his bunch. The first to catch his eye was Zerkernaut, a giant of a troll, clad in the spiky thorny armor that was favored by his kind. Toadentrop had to chuckle to him self as he thought, "he is actually trying to blend into the background and be inconspicuous."  Just to the right of Zerkernaut was Shimmian a tall half elven woodsman from the Qeynos hills. He too was trying to be nonchalant, leaning on his great ash bow as if he weren't terrified of the din that was at the heart of the city. To the left of  Shimmian was Lady Esme. As she stood in the square, all three foot nine inches of her,  she amongst the group seemed the most at ease. All the same it was clear to Toadentrop that Esme would rather not be here. <br>Standing in front of the group with arms crossed, was a wood elf  maid,  the scowl on her face made her usually fawney eyes look hard and sharp. Her chestnut hair and sun-browned cheeks reminded him of a face he'd seen long ago, but that was a far away place and this was after all her sister, Mythrial.<br><br>"I will have words with you, Toadentrop," she said calmly.<br><br>Changing the subject he knew would do him no good, "stand your ground,"he thought, "that what Dwarven warriors do best." Steeling himself he said, "My gear's all packed, I've got my passage, I'm going."<br><br>At that Lady Esme piped up and asked in her strong voice, "Why?"<br><br>Toadentrop fumbled about in his head for an answer, just one answer but he could not. <br><br>Before he could frame a thought in his head Shimmian said, "the Lad Looks thirsty, I'm thirsty. Let's talk this over, over an ale or two, over yonder," pointing to Powel's pub with the end of his bow, "The troll's buying."<br><br>"Huh?" was about all Zerkernaut could say before the ranger started herding the group into the bar.<br>The ranger had chosen well for the place was not crouded and the group quickly found a place to sit, save Zerkernaut who chose not to test the strength of the chair and opted to stand. <br>The whole time Toadentrop could feel Esme's and Mythrials eyes on him, burning holes in his very being.<br>Shimmian motioned to the barmaid, "Dwarven Ale's all around."<br><br>At  this Toadentrop stood apologizing, "I really must board my ship..."<br><br>"Nonsense!" laughed Shimmian, "there is plenty of time before the ship sails. Plenty of time to tell us why you wish to go." <br><br>" Yes, tell me Dear heart, why do you wish to go off and get yourself killed?" asked Mythrial.<br><br>"It's a war!, in my home, Your home Milady, " Toadentrop started to say.<br><br>"You don't know that." interrupted Esme.<br><br>"Milady, I have heard, you yourself  heard Lady Lyrikal's report about The Crushbone..."<br><br>"They don't know it was Emporer Crushbone's Orcs."  interrupted Esme.<br><br>"It was Crush alright, it has the smell of Crush." Said Toadentrop<br>At that moment Toadentrop heard The Troll snort. he got a puzzled look on his face  and then began to speak. "Whut you Do when You gets der.?" asked the troll.<br><br>"I will Join the..." started Toadentrop.<br><br>"Stormguard, and defend Kaladim from the evil marauding Orc legionaries... and get yourself cut to pieces or blown to flinders by some Orc Shaman." Interrupted Mythrial.<br><br>"Milady..." started Toad.<br><br>"That place isn't your home anymore, dear Toadentrop, you have a home here with us now...  Why are you so determined to get ..." interjected Esme.<br><br>"Neither was the Kith Milady, when the dead walked in the Forrest's of Kith, who was the first to rally to your cry?" said Toad proudly. <br><br>"Nay it wasn't and Aye you were, but it I spent 2 seasons nursing you back to health from the wounds you got there, and you still walk with a limp." Said Mythrial. "Why had it not been for Shimmian here you would be wandering the forrest now as a haunted spirit. You Blasted Fool!"ranted Mythrial," You heard Zerkernaut call the retreat, and you stood your ground!" as She continued she began to punctuate each word  by slamming her fist onto the table," Stubbornness Is not heroic! Its Foolish! I know you! You will get into battle and when things start to go badly the Watch captain will call a retreat and you will insist on being the rear guard and hold them while the rest retire. You will be dead, because you are stubborn." <br>By now there was more beer on the table than in the mugs.<br><br>"She's right you know," said Esme. "What good will one more sword do on any account?"<br><br>"Lord Irone went, and don't just say that He's Just another sword." Said the Dwarf.<br>Shimmian got pale and replied, "Aye, and he hasn't been heard from since"<br><br>"Da Stormguard is tough, but iffn da word I herd is, da Tree City is Gone, da whole Wood elf  army gone, fey burnin n black, Ifn dat so, nuttin gonna stop Crush." stated the Troll.<br>As Zerkernaut spoke Toadentrop noticed  tears welling up in Mythrial's eye. It seemed to the dwarf that the She-elven Druidess really did care deeply about her homeland. <br><br>"Don't tell me, err,  us that Lady Lyrikal has put you  up to this." scolded Mythrial. "I'll..."<br><br>"You'll what?" Asked Esme. "Let us all just calm ourselves a moment... this is serious business and serious business is for cool heads. That goes especially for you." Directing her last comment at the dwarf.<br><br>"We all appreciate your Loyalty to your Patron and his Wife, but" started Shimmian<br><br>"No, no 'Buts' and yes,  Some of why I go is for Lady Lyrikal's sake, though she never bid me so, and knowing her, were she to know I was Bound for Kaladim she would be here at this table trying to stop me." pleaded Toadentrop. "Whilst I was Lady Lyrikal's sword theign, and shield, I faced many dangers, but not out of obligation, out of love and respect for my Master,and his charge. Why it was Lady Lyrikal that Introduced me to you Dear  Mythrial , and," Toadentrop paused, "your sister Illiamian."<br><br>"I remember that day, my father despised you, but out of difference to the Song Mistress Lyrikal tolerated you." said Mythrial "Illiamain, LilKitty, was fascinated by you. I was trying to get ready for my first trip across the sea to converse with the treants of  South Karana, and all she did was pester me about you. That day... Twas the last I saw of her."<br><br>"Aye," Said Toadentrop, "and I am sorry."<br> <br>There was a long silence, just enough time for a tear to roll down Toadentrop's face. it was this that caused the Troll to speak."Toad, you naut resp... resp... tu blame fer Lilkitty's death, Orc's Kill her She go in look araound get caught get killd, Shalisar tell me, You tried hard rescue her while she Livin, then almost die yerself gettin her body so's Orc's not disp... disop... desecret... ruin her body. Dat brave, stupid, but brave enough." <br><br>Toadentrop sat  with a glazed expression on his face gazing into Mythrial's eyes. <br><br>Esme touched the dwarf  on his shoulder and asked, "Are you Alright?"He tugged at his braided beard to steel himself. Esme continued, "Good squire, When I found you Lost and hungry in Freeport you told me that you had to find a druidess  in these lands, when I told you, you were fortunate enough to find one, you did not laugh, it was then that I knew that your travels were of  a serious nature, Twas then you told me you bore a message for Mythrial daughter  to Eldwith and Irenith." Esme paused, "The dread news, and important names clouded my mind a bit. but I can see you now as you were then, your beard sir, twas braided as it is now..." All eyes were directed at long black strands dangling from the dwarf's chin. "Tis the way an Elf maid marks her bo,  braids in her love's hair, is it not? Elven Love braids? At the time I had not seen many of your kind and thought nothing of it, but now, Squire, I have never seen any Dwarf with beard braided so."<br><br>Mythrial Raised an eyebrow. <br><br>Esme continued, "Good squire, there is more to this. A tale to tell perhaps, Hmmm?" There was a pause and Esme prodded Toadentrop, "Come Sir, if we are to send you off to your certain death we must know this. Lest the story perish with you, sounds to me to be an epic tale, would be a shame were it to die with ye."<br><br>The first words from Toadentrop's lips were, "Dear lady, I am sorry" It seemed to Toadentrop that those were the words he greeted lady Mythrial every chance they met. Yet he continued, "That day and the days after were the happiest in my life, and the saddest." the dwarf paused to sip his beer. "After we conducted you to the port and put you on that ship, Lady Mythrial,  I thought I would never see The misty woodlands of your home again. but for some reason my mistress had business in the Tree city. It suited me just fine while Lady Lyrikal was in conference or just in the city she would dismiss me for a time. and that left me free to explore. On the very first adventure through the wood, I came upon Illiamian.  Or rather, was ambushed by Illiamian, for she was a master of concealment and sprang upon me unawares. I can still smell the honeysuckle in her hair..."<br><br>The Troll Snorted and snuffed... "Me think Dwarf make that up. All me smell is Beer and Hobbit feets."<br>At that Esme shot an Icy look at the Troll.<br><br>"Please continue" Said Mythrial. her soft brown eyes narrowing on the dwarf.<br><br>Toadentrop explained, "We tumbled about in the moss and fallen leaves, at first I struggled but when I knew <br>what or rather who had pounced on me I relented. At that Illiamian said, 'Huh! Some great dwarven warrior you are!' and then she laughed, twas  a musical laughter that rings in your heart, I knew I was falling in love. She teased me yet again "had I been an Orc You'd have been  dead. I said, ' perhaps lady' it was when i tried to address her in her Elven name  which was hard for me  to pronounce, that she bade me address her as Lilkitty."  Toadentrop continued " I explained that I had slain many orcs and this was true, orc pawns are still orcs, to which she replied 'the mighty Dwarf protector needs a protector' and she smiled. Twas that moment the Orc chose to interrupt our chat. He grabbed and scratched at my Lilkitty, and I leapt. Two short strokes with my blade and the orc was slain. She was shaken but unharmed. I honestly do not know who was more frightened, yet we laughed. I told her that she needed a protector too. she assured me that she was safe the whole time. She giggled and cast a spell, there was a flash and she was gone."<br><br>Mythrial interrupted , "Father would not let us play in the glade until we had learned the spell of escape." <br><br>Toadentrop continued, "In the days that followed, Lady Lyrikal had many more conferences, and so I had free time to spare, and each day I spent with Lilkitty. We would dine on the forrest berries,  frolic and play,  one particular game was our favorite, Hide and seek. Milady was an expert at hiding I truly believe even a scent hound would not have found her had she wished it. I might spend an hour looking only to have her spring from her hiding place and catch me unawares. Twas during such a game  that we encountered Shalisar the Wolf prince. I was routing about through ferns seeking My dear Lilkitty, when I  hear a booming voice, "Stand and be recognized!' I stood slowly so as not to startle my challenger. Must be My quarry too decided to stand, as she emerged beside me, for I heard  a peal of joyous booming laughter. They spoke in a tongue I did not understand. After a few moments Lilkitty started to speak in common and said to <br>the man, 'Lord Shalisar of The Hallas Wastes, please meet and greet  master Toadentrop Sword Theign to Lyrikal Song mistress Of Kethen.' It was then That Shalisar bowed before me. The Great Shalisar! I nearly fell over dead." Toadentrop excitedly continued. "I do not know if I spoke or just stood and shook... he laughed and spoke more to Lilkitty and then turned to me and warned  not to stray too far from the Glade that we were close to The Crush and dare not go any closer as there was trouble brewing. I thanked him and he said some words in parting to Lilkitty, and we were alone again. So we found a Sunny hillock to sit upon and we began one of our long talks, this was an important day,and I had important news that I was reluctant to divulge, but as we talked Lilkitty began to braid my beard. as she did so she sang a soft song... almost in whispers, as she worked I drifted and dreamed, and when she was done she announced that she knew that Lady Lyrikal's business was almost complete and that since we would be apart for a bit she was going to mark me. i knew not what she meant but was relieved that she knew and was not too saddened, that it would be some time before we could meet again. She Laughed and pushed me over and said 'One last Game of Hide  and seek! If you can find me, you can kiss me!'"<br><br>Shimmian asked, "how did you know she had hidden in the Crushbone pass?"<br><br>Tears were welling up in Toadentrop's eyes, "Alas she was not, but I did not know the lands, and I was determined  to find and win my kiss. So as I wandered and sought I had the misfortune upon finding the pass to the Crush. I knew not where I was, yet I had heard Shalisar's warning, but fool that I am I heeded it not. A kiss from an angel was worth any danger to me, and surely Lilkitty would not hide anywhere dangerous, I thought to myself. The whole experience was surreal I knew not of the danger I was in until it was suddenly upon me... As I wandered about seeking Milady I had passed and not noticed two Orc Centurions and an Orc Shaman. They, however knew of me and were setting me up for some vicious trap no doubt, for a thick misty fog started rolling in about me. Just as The centurion was about to grasp me I heard  Lilkitty cry, 'Look Out behind you!'" At that moment she emerged from some thick brush. I turned and pushed the beast into the Orc shaman who was casting some foul spell that was producing more fog. Some how the second centurion  leapt passed me and straight at Lilkitty. As I Drew my blade I knew I would never close the distance before the Orc would be on her and this was no pawn brandishing its's claws this was a full grown centurion armed with a wicked Spear. I was relieved as I saw Milady start to cast. Ahh my love will escape I thought,  She was staring at me, I knew I was doomed, but I would go down fighting  and My love would be safe. The last friendly face I would see would be hers, it was then that she completed her incantation."<br><br>"A Fissel?" Lady Esme Asked excitedly.<br><br>Toadentrop's face was pale and ghastly, "Just as Lilkitty finished her incantation there was A stroke of lightening behind me, and I was awash in orc Blood and cinders. The Orcs behind me must have been back on their feet and after me,  It seemed the whole world stood still  a split second later, I saw...." Toadentrop was shaking now, "The orc stabbed... The spear was buried deeply into her chest, and she grasped the spear tightly as she fell. I could.. her rasping breath... The Orc grinned and turned on me, He had been disarmed but he was determined to kill me too. much of that battle I do not remember after the first blow, but some how I survived. I stood over the broken orc's body and shivered. The mist was thick and now though I could not see them I heard the din and shouts of the denizens of Crush, they were out  to find the source of the commotion. in the midst of this I heard... Milady forgive me, I heard that rasping breath..." I began to feel about in the mist for the my fallen love, when There was a pair of huge hands about me and suddenly I was being hauled upon an immense man's shoulder at a full run."<br><br>Toadentrop buried his face in his hands a moment, "I struggled at first thinking I was Being born into Crush castle, it was then when I noticed the my captor, was wearing not orc armor but a wolf skin cape, and was being shot full of arrows as he ran. Shalisar had heard Lilkitty's lightening stroke and ran in to assist. Only to find me  about to be overwhelmed. He did what he could he grabbed me and effected an escape. I know not how he kept his feet, or what magic kept him alive even but  suddenly I heard the song of lady Lyrikal.<br>Shalisar fell to his knee's and set me down. the great lady asked if I was hurt, I said no. She asked where Mistress Illiamian was, my tear was enough of a reply.  'Dread things happen to those that fall in the Valley of Crush,  We must... recover or destroy the body, lest Illiamian become a banshee, a tourchered spirit doomed to immortal torment.' That was enough for me. I shall go, I told her. I will save her spirit or die trying. <br>"You will need help." she said. and with that she drew the great sword at Shalisar's side and handed it to me."<br><br>There was a gasp throughout the room. <br><br>"I did not know it at the time but in my hands was the sword of souls. In my hands was a weapon that gave me some of the strength from each of the thousands of victims slain by the blade. Had I known I held such a weapon I might not have entered  the Crush valley  to keep the blade from falling into vile hands. Yet I did not know. Again I was in a surreal state. I knew only one thing, find my love. I know not how but when next I saw Lady Lyrikal I was carrying the broken form of my lady over my shoulder much the way Shalisar had done me and I was handing the sword back to the great lady.  I saw Shalisar sleeping quietly  apparently out of deaths grip, Only then did I collapse."<br><br>"When I awoke I was in a house in the trees, there was much sadness at the funeral. the whole city turned out all dressed in black. and under a starry sky Illiamian Druidess Of the Greater Fey, was laid to rest at the base of a Great oak." <br><br>"A sadder tale could not be told." shuddered Esme drying tears  with a kerchief.<br><br>Mythrial sat speechless.<br><br>"I am sorry Milady,  That day your sister, my love, gave her life to save me, rather than escape, and I failed her, I believe though she was dyeing she lived still when I was wisked away. I am sorry...." Toadentrop fell to his knees. "Twas that day that I vowed that I should never retreat until the fallen have been recovered, and the injured are safe. I will not fail, I will not betray milady's gift again... I cannot hide here in safety while the lands  of  my dearest love are imprisoned. ...Oh my, I am so sorry...."<br><br>Mythrial cradled Toadentrop's head in her lap and began to cry. <br><br>"Silly Dwarf," she said between her tears, "you know you should have bought enough passes for the five of us ."<br><br>              *               *               *             *            *          *           *           *           *           *           *<br><br>The bell on the Aria tolled three times as a warning that the ship would soon depart. Five figures  stood on the main deck at the rail each looking at the city of Freeport as if it might be the last time they saw it. Two amongst them were probably the most uneasy about the departure, the tallest, Zerkernaut, and the shortest, lady Esme. Doublely so for they were leaving the land of their birth,  to travel to a place where few or none of their kind dwelt. <br><br>Just as the Aria's bell began to toll again, there was an obvious commotion on the docks. A tall man wearing  a wolf pelt cloak raced to the end of the pier. The ship was already cast off and  more that ten strides from the end of the dock. The man with mad determination leapt arms flailing and landed rolling on the deck. <br><br>"You didn't expect to sneak off and save Fedwer without me?" panted Shalisar.<br><br>A puzzled look appeared on Toadentrop's face.<br><br> "Lady Lyrikal thought you might try some fool's errand and asked me to keep an eye out for you, and aye, before you ask, she asked me to stop you, but I know my heart, and I know yours is no less. I cannot bring myself to do as she bids." said the nomad prince between breaths.<br><br>"How did you know I would be leaving this day, from here?" wondered the dwarf.<br><br>Shalisar chuckled, "Just how many trolls walk about freely in Freeport?" Looking at Zerkernaut, "How are you My good Runt?" Turning back to Toadentrop, "Just how many travel in the company of a dwarf lad? T'was easy enough to ponder out your plan." <br><br>"We are honored to have you in our midst," said Esme with a bow.<br><br>Shimmian nudged Toadentrop and pointed out the ship's steward and master at arms were approaching. "Right. I must ask to show me your boarding pass sir." said the Steward.<br><br>"I have none." said Shalisar.<br><br>The Master at arms bristled, "Then I must ask you to..."<br><br>"It's all right he can stay," the captain called down from the Aft-deck, "he can keep an eye on that troll. Now, back to work! Steward, check the stores  and see to the cargo. Mister Ager, see to the watch, there will be a full moon and that means the furies will be sporting about!"<br>With that the crew set about their work.<br><br>"Aye, Runt, you better stay in line," Shalisar laughed.<br><br>"Me do." laughed Zerkernaut.<br><br>And so he company cast one last silent gaze at the city disappearing into the distance and decided to wander below decks to find accommodations. Normally even though the Aria was a large ship, the passengers were often asked to share cabins. T his was not the case on this voyage. It seemed the crossing's popularity had faded since the outbreak of war. With the exception of Zerkernaut who preferred the open air of the fore-deck, each made them selves at home in their own cabin. The ward room where they were to take their meals was large considering it was aboard a ship. The food was fair if a bit plain, and lacking variety. For they served fish chowder and flat bread for lunch and supper and  breakfast was flat bread with either berry preserves or clover honey.  <br><br>On the second night, over the evening meal,  Esme broke the silence, "I should hope we make good time, my stomach is not..."<br><br>"It's not my stomach objecting," interrupted Mythrial. "Fish chowder... makes one wonder what kind of fish..."<br><br>"Mmm naut bad," slurped the troll, "Taste like toad." with that came the sound of five spoons being dropped into their bowls. "MMmmm you mind if I finish yers?" asked Zerkernaut motioning to Mythrial with is spoon.<br><br>Silently and with visible disgust Mythrial pushed her bowl over for the troll.<br><br>For a time the group sat in silent horror as Zerkernaut ate, and it was Shimmian who broke the din silence by asking, "Well, this seems to be an ideal time for me to quench a curiosity of mine.<br>You see I am student of language, and of culture, yet I must confess your name has been a bit of a puzzle to me, lad." Looking straight at the dwarf, "It means Falling Frog? How did you land yourself a moniker like that?"<br><br>"Frogs falling actually." Esme interjected.<br><br>"Aye, to speak it plainly, tis true, my name means frogs falling." The dwarf  answered.<br><br>Hiding a smile Mythrial prodded, "And...."<br><br>"I was named by those that found me, you see I was born and orphaned on the same day. On the same day... " reflected the dwarf. "I am told that  the day before King Xobe and the vast Runny Eyed goblin tribe were defeated and forced to flee The Butcher Block, there was  a huge storm. A storm the likes of which none has seen before or since. Great winds and thunder roared  through the valley of Kaladim.  In the flat beyond the city gates there once was a small trading villiage. The storm laid waste to it and killed most of those that lived there.<br>The hail and wind and rain was too much for the wood framed huts that most had built there. Oddly, and cruelly it seemed that the gods has played a jest on the peoples there, for along with the hailstones, and inside some were frogs... thousands of frogs. <br> My mother's broken body was found  in the rubble that was the villiage, clinging to her newborn son. I was born before a great bitter-sweet victory for my people. I was born on a day that was unforgettable, and to be sure my foster parents placed the responsibility of commemorating the day on me... I was born on the day It stormed so hard that Frogs fell from the heavens..."<br><br>The table suddenly rumbled, as Zerkernaut belched. When he was finished he smiled and said, "You  alot like me den,  you named troll fashioned. You have good name."<br><br>Coughing and waving his hand before his face, Shimmian asks,"Lord Zerkernaut, your name is a puzzle to me as well."<br><br>Shalisar clears his throat a bit and begins to laugh.<br><br>"I'm not as familiar with the language of trolls as i should be," starts Mythrial, "Zer... small I think" <br><br>"Ker?  Is it pup? Cub?" Esme interrupts, "Smallest Pup... but the last of it is a puzzle."<br><br>Shimmian "RUNT? Thats your name? You have to be the biggest Troll I have ever seen!"<br><br>Shalisar chuckled, "Aye, he is no longer a Runt, but since there is no word in troll for no longer, The Runt became  Runt Not, Zerkernaut... You have to understand our troll  friend here was not raised in Oggok  by his mother.  Mygatz bore three that spring, a large brood for trollkind. Zerkernaut's other two brood-brothers  were big and strong, green and scaley from the start,  Zerker here was tiny, and grey, just clinging to life for the first days. Mygatz faced a tough choice for her littlest one. It is common for Troll runts to be torn to bits and eaten by their broodmates or even their older siblings. Sometimes to save the welp from suffering  the mother of a sickly trolling will eat it on the spot.<br><br>Esme turned very pale at this and  Mythrial looked as if she was about to wretch, "That is horrid!"<br><br>"Aye it may seem that way to you, but troll kind live in a hard place. They live by hard rules. It is as it is. so that they can live in their land. Trolls are not evil by nature, they just have a strong will to live, and will do shocking things to stay alive. Oft times a person will have an ill run in with trolls in their homeland, simply because  to most trolls if it lets you eat it, it's food." explained Shalisar. "I was saying, Mygatz had a tough choice,  I came accross whilst I was wandering the Inthule on an errand for a friend. I had never beheld a weeping troll. I asked why she wept. Mygatz told me of her intention to abandon her welp to save it from her other children. She could not eat her son, and could not protect him from her kind. So I took the welp.  I  told her that he would be safe and that I would find someone to raise him. So it was that I bore our friend here to Ixucha." <br><br>Shimmian's Eyes widened, "The Witch of Inthule?"<br><br>"Aye," replied Shalisar. <br><br>"Tog'tog Ixucha, be outcast like me, she make gud mom for me. Feed me. Make me swim. Make me break wood. She teach, me learn. Onlyiest troll I see for two springs was Tog'tog. Shalisar teached me too. When I ask why I seen no other like me day say cause I'm Zerker," said the troll.<br><br>"Then there came the day that your brother's  Yerpes and Uganh, discovered that your mother had broken troll-law by letting you live, " continued Shalisar. "Mygatz paid for that crime by being eaten."  <br><br>Toadentrop grasped his eathenware mug so tightly that it crumbled spilling the sour ale he was drinking all over the table.<br><br>"Uganh was not satisfied with half justice, so he set out to find the meal  he was denied as a welp. He roamed deep into the Swamp to find Zerker here," continued Shalisar. " Find him he did." <br><br>"I were breakin wood for da fire when I hear dis chunchin splashin roar.  I looked and I see A troll runnin at me. Me start to say hey an da cleaver Uganh was swingin hacked into me. Me think Uganh was suprised when cleaver stuck on my shoulder and not come free. Me slamm da air outta him an he leggo of da cleaver. <br>When he get back up he start claw'n and punchen.  I slamm agin, and he fall, he back up, claw, I slamm he fall agin. Dis time he fall hard I tink he trip on broke up wood. I look an it worse, he fell on broken off tree da stump is sticken true his back an outta his belly. Me never see'd so much blood.  He point at cleaver and ask why I not dead yet. He say It poisoned, I should be dead... I ask him why he kill me an He tell me bout Mother, an Yerpes, and den Uganh cough the black blood, an died. Me not know much o wut happen next. Me feel weak an sick Me wander off to find Tog'tog..."<br><br>"You wandered off? I found you in the desert of North Ro, shivvering and delerious from poison. You mean to tell me you got that Cleaver cut in The Swamp of Inthule? You must have walked for 4 days to get where I found you!" exclaimed Mythrial. <br><br>"Me remember you dat day, me tink me dead and gone to...  Me never see'd a Elfie before..." said Zerkernaut. <br><br>"How ironic, The first Troll he'd ever met tried to kill him, and the first Elf he met saved his life." interjected Esme. "Just one think still, you said you lived with Ixucha for two springs after you were born so... and you have been traveling with Mythrial for a year now... You are three Years old?" <br><br>Shalisar laughs, "Three and a half now. Trolls grow up very fast."<br><br>The group began to laugh, but was cut short by a clamor above deck.<br><br>The Aria's bell rang loudly and the master at arms could be heard barking instructions for the crew to take arms.<br><br>Shimmian, being closest to the door was the first on deck. Springing behind him was Shalisar. Mythrial, Esme and Toadentrop brought up the rear.  The Fury's ship was long sleek and bone grey.  The Aria was a swift ship under full sail but by some cruel twist of fate they were becalmed, The oars of the fury craft were beating the water  like a wasp's wings. The distance closed rapidly. <br><br>"Why do we just sit here?" asked Esme.<br><br>"We are becalmed, there is no wind. No wind in the sails and we go nowhere..." shouted the Captain.<br><br>Mythrial looked at Esme and without words it seemed they knew eachother's thought. They Grasped hands and began the chant.<br><br>Closing now the ships were within bowshot of eachother and so Shimmian began to shoot. and the furies replied. Esme was nearly struck by an arrow as the two continued their labor, chanting and circling with arms intertwined. The wind  started first as a faint gust of a breeze, then grew. As the Sails filled the ship bagan to move. It seemed they would be saved. Still The fury ship closed. Toadentrop looked at Shalisar and the look in his eyes told him that they would be boarded...<br><br><br>The crew of the Aria rushed to arm themselves, but belaying pins and a few cutlasses in the hands of  the crewmen would  not be enough to keep the ship from being taken. As the grappling hooks started <br>flying  Toadentrop  felt   his stomach welling up in is throat.  The Fury's ship was close enough  so that he could see  whom he was about to face.  he had heard about  the horrid  ghoulish mermen  that plain folk  called sea furies, but he never expected to see any. Green slimey skin stretched over a short very muscular frame, dark dead eyes, and snapping jaws filled with needle like fanglets, made thies  creatures as horrid to look at as they were deadly. To add  insult to injury, each was armed with either a stout steel blade and a shield  or an oddly shaped bow and arrows. Zerkernaut stormed accross the deck chopping the entangleing lines  from the enemy ship. For every one he cut  it seemed  three more  would  strike the deck.<br><br>The ships drew together with a crash and there arose a deep warbling warcry from the Furies.  Toadentrop planted his feet on the deck deliberately  between  the Fury ship and the druidesses. Suddenly over the rail of the Aria came a wave of furies. The young dwarf  felt  the moments distill down, as if time  had slowed.<br>Toadentrop watched as Zerkernaut, Shalisar, and Shimmian threw themselves on the first throng. The crew rallied  and pressed the invaders back but at a horrid cost. Again  the Cry  came from the Deck of the Fury ship and again the dark green forms launched themselves  over the rail with steel and Fangs flashing. This time there were fewre defenders to throw them back.  The line seemed to have broken and A pair of furies rushed  right at Lady Mythrial and Esme. Toadentrop buried the point of his sword into the first  and  wheeled  about throwing  the crumpled  form into the rushing second. The acrid smell of the creatures blood stung has he breathed. The other regained it's feet and scrambled  to get  the lady druids. The young dwarf  hurled himself  on the back of the creature  and was surprised to see that it was already dead  slashed nearly in twain by Lady Mythrial's  scimitar.  Looking back  Toadentrop saw that the second wave  had been thrown back. Some of the crewmen that had fallen  and some of the wounded  were dragged  overboard  by retreating furies. Their  cries and a sickening munching sound could be heard  from  the deck of the fury ship.<br> <br>Toadentrop glanced about. he could see Zerkernaut, bleeding from a wound  in is left arm. Shimmian scratched and bleeding horridly, and Shalisar. Shalisar seemed to be un hurt, a blessing at least. But there were  few others standing to meet the inevitable third wave.  As the gurgling roar began on the ship below, Toaden heard a desperate chant from behind him. The flash blinded friend and foe alike for some time. Lady Esme's lightening bolt struck near the bow of the fury ship and lady Mythrial's  near the aft. The Air hung with the stench of ozone, and burnt flesh. Taking advantage of the chaos Zerkernaut who seemed  not to have been blinded  started to cut the lines. The Fury ship was ablaze and drifting off...  To all the battle seemed to have been won. Toadentrop  could see  a curious movement on the deck of the crippled  Raider craft. The furies scrambled to  uncover a large device on the aft deck of the ship. A war engine, like a gigantic crossbow... It was unlimbered and  set. Toaden stood shocked as it was pointed directly at him it seemed. Shalisar lept a mighty leap  as the giant bowstring  sung.  A huge black iron tipped spear pierced  Shalisar in mid leap directly before Toadentrop's eye's.  A fine mist of blood  coated Toadentrop as Shalisar crumpled to the deck.  The blade in the wolf princes hand skiddered from his grasp to a stop at The Dwarf's feet.  Toadentrop rushed to the fallen prince. There in a pool of his own blood  the noble Prince Shalisar breathed his last  breath  in the arms  of the young dwarf.  Already So much death, death of friends and loved ones had visited Toadentrop, his tears left pale streaks on his blood painted face. Lady Mythrial  pulled the Body from Toadentrop's arms. Only then did  he turn his attention to the long silvery blade  on the deck..<br><br>It seemed as if all  eye's on the ship were on him. Toadentrop picked up the sword of souls. Looking up  he caught the proud look on Lady Esme's face. Strangely he felt numb as he strode to the rail and looked out at the Fury ship as it rolled over and sank smouldering into the chruning sea. The look of pride In Esme's eyes turned to shock as it did  in all the eyes  of those watching...  <br>Toadentrop strode right up to The Troll and pressed the hilt of the blade into  Zerkernaut's hand. "with this blade, no Orc or army of Orcs  could stand against you." <br><br>And  so it was that the most powerful weapon in the history of Norrath passed into the hands of a troll, the largest troll ever to stride.

