<P>
	What is this thing we call Everquest?  What is it we pour our money and our time in an almost religious manner day in and day out?  Some call it a game, but what kind of game?  Is it a 3D &#8220;shooter&#8221; where you go out and blast everything to kingdom come and check your score at the end to compare and contrast it to someone else&#8217;s?  Or maybe it is a real-time strategy where you must analyze your opponent&#8217;s weakness and choose your choice approach, style of combat, choice of weapons, and if needed, method of escape.  Maybe it is none of these things.  Maybe it is all of them.  But maybe, just maybe, it is something combining all, and much more.<br><br>	An environment where the user plays a role of his or her choice, that is what I would think would best describe this phenomena we call Everquest.  It was even marketed as, &#8220;a 3D massively multiplayer on-line fantasy role-playing game.&#8221;  But in the aftermath of the rush to get in an experience this game, we find a continuation of the question of, &#8220;What does role-playing mean,&#8221; and the argument, &#8220;You can&#8217;t tell me how to play this game.&#8221;<br><br>	Those that question what roleplaying is are on the right track with the vision of the game itself, how to take your views of life and self and transplant them into a persona that varies from exactly like you to drastically different from you.  &#8220;What does roleplaying mean?&#8221;  It means to alter your perception and put yourself into a world that is not your own.  In this case, you are a person in a world of swords and sorcery, might and magic, and &#8220;good&#8221; versus &#8220;evil.&#8221;  As long as can remember that, leave &#8220;real life&#8221; behind then you are roleplaying.  If real life must come into your conversation, indicate it some how, normally with the acronym OOC (Out Of Character) and say what you must, then you can state you are roleplaying again with the acronym IC (In Character).<br><br>	Those that argue that no one can tell them how to play are, in all essence, wrong.  That is to say they are not wrong, just their perspective of the environment is wrong.  If you were to go out and play soccer with your hands or football with a bat, you would be considered crazy.  Hard core fans of those sports would be insulted that you would actually try to alter their game by changing the &#8220;spirit&#8221; of the game.  What is so different about on-line gaming from real life gaming that the &#8220;spirit&#8221; of the game must be so flexible to the thousands?<br><br>	Maybe because the arena in which the game is play is so new that the &#8220;spirit&#8221; has yet to be formed, but this is not likely.  Roleplaying has been around and is established and taking it to the computer gaming world is not new either.  What is new, however, is this new form of the game. <br><br>	A first-person view to combat from using an array of weapons and tactics against large numbers of foes&#8230;sounds familiar.  The 3D shooter fans see something in this new game that they like and they bring their views of gaming to this environment without fully understanding what they are getting into.  They believe that the game can be &#8220;beaten&#8221; by advancing to the highest level and slaying the most potent opponent there is, and the first one to do it wins the game.  Even if they deny it, the drive is there.  Who has not gone out to their friends and bragged that
